<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bhutan Exhibition to Be Hosted In India Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A major exhibition of Bhutan,
the first of its kind in more than a decade, will be hosted in
India between October and November 2001, a joint press release by
both countries said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the exhibition was a result of an official
goodwill visit to India by Bhutanese Foreign Minister Lyonpo Jigmi
Y. Thinley, which started on April 17 and ends on Thursday, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
With a theme of "The Living Religious and Cultural Tradition of
Bhutan," the exhibition will focus mainly on Buddhism in Bhutan,
Buddhist ritual performances, arts, crafts and architecture of
Bhutan and Bhutanese performing arts.
</P>
<P>
According to the initial schedule, the exhibition will be held
in New Delhi and Calcutta for a period of two weeks in each
location, said the release.
</P>
<P>
Thinley, who is paying his first official visit to India, met
Indian President K.R. Narayanan, Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee, his Indian counterpart External Affairs Minister Jaswant
Singh and several other Indian cabinet members during his 10-day
stay, the release said.
</P>
<P>
During these meetings, both sides reviewed and expressed
satisfaction at the wide-ranging cooperation between the two
countries, and agreed to continue to closely consult and cooperate
with each other on issues of mutual interest, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese foreign minister also invited Jaswant Singh to
visit Bhutan within this year and the latter accepted the
invitation, said the release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
