<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Reaffirms Help to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan reiterated its pledge to
extend cooperation to Bangladesh and expressed the hope that the
South Asian country will soon cross the least-developed country (
LDC) period through economic development, a senior Japanese
official told reporters here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Bangladesh at the head of a 10-member consultation
delegation, Yutaka Yokoi, director of the loan aid division in the
Economic Cooperation Bureau of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
said many factors contribute to the positive attitude of Japan in
its commitment for economic development of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said Japan has formulated country aid plan (CAP) in
conformity with Overseas Development Assistance Charter of 1992
for Bangladesh, Vietnam, Thailand, the Philippines, Egypt, Ghana,
Kenya, Tanzania and Peru.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthening relations with Bangladesh will contribute to
Japan's relations with the LDCs and also to political stability in
South Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out priority areas for Japanese assistance, Yokoi said
projects related to agriculture, rural development, productivity
improvement, improvement of basic living standards, health care,
basic infrastructure for investment and export promotion and
disaster management were earmarked as the key issues to be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
However, he said a 0.2 percent cut was made in the overseas
development assistance as Japan is under pressure to ensure
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Yokoi said that until 1998, Japan's overseas development
assistance disbursement to Bangladesh includes 3 billion U.S.
dollars as loan aid and 2.8 billion dollars in the form of grant
aid and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said a Japanese appraisal mission will arrive in Dhaka in
early May to evaluate and determine the volume of assistance for
Bangladesh in the next fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
