<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Calls MPF Crucial Step in Providing Retirement Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The implementation of the
Mandatory Provident Fund (MPF) schemes in December this year is an
important step in providing the workforce with a retirement
protection system, a Hong Kong official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon hosted by the Rotary Club, MPF Executive
Director Hendena Yu said the introduction of MPF "will mean that
for the first time in Hong Kong, employers will be required by law
to make contributions for their employees' retirement benefits."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the workforce will also have to save for their old
age," she said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to suggestions that the MPF system should be
deferred, Yu reiterated that it was not in the interest of
employees to delay the system.
</P>
<P>
"MPF schemes are long-term investments and in order to
accumulate a sufficient amount of funds to meet their needs after
retirement, it is important for employers, employees and self-
employed persons to start making contributions as early as
practicable.
</P>
<P>
"Delaying the commencement of MPF contributions would only
reduce the amount of funds available at retirement," she said.
</P>
<P>
Yu also stressed that the MPF was never meant to replace the
existing Comprehensive Social Security Assistance (CSSA) Scheme.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that MPF and CSSA are indeed complementary to each
other in protecting the old," she said.
</P>
<P>
"With the introduction of MPF, Hong Kong will have in place all
the three retirement protection 'pillars' recommended by the World
Bank, namely a mandatory, privately managed retirement protection
system, a publicly financed social security system and voluntary
personal savings and insurance," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
