<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua)-- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua here today:
</P>
<P>
 Vice-President Meets Slovakia Defense Minister
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao, also vice-chairman of the
Central Military Commission, in meeting with Slovak Defense
Minister Pavol Kanis, said that China appreciates Slovakia's
adherence to the "one China" policy and its efforts to develop
ties with China.
</P>
<P>
 Vice-Premier Meets U.S. Minister
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao said that a clear-cut and
unconditional settlement of the permanent normal trade relations (
PNTR) issue will be good both for China and the United States, in
meeting with U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
 China, EU to Resume WTO Talks
</P>
<P>
China and the European Union have agreed to begin a new round
of talks concerning China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) in the week beginning May 15, the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation announced.
</P>
<P>
Senior U.S. Official Urges Granting China PNTR Status
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman encouraged
the local U.S. business community to support the granting of the
Permanent Normal Trading Relations (PNTR) status for China, when
addressing the U.S. business people at a luncheon held by the
American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
FM Spokesman Reiterates China's Stand
</P>
<P>
in Response to Japanese PM's Remarks
</P>
<P>
In response to Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori's remarks
that whether or not Japan carried out an invasion should be judged
by people in the process of history, Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Sun Yuxi on Tuesday urged Japan to learn profound
lessons from Japan's history of invasion.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that the director-general of Asian affairs
division of the Japanese Foreign Ministry, at the direction of
Yoshiro Mori, met with Chinese diplomats stationed in Japan and
made clarification on Mori's remarks.
</P>
