<HEADLINE> Leaving Imperial Park Understandable: Kentucky Fried Chicken (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kentucky Fried Chicken
Corporation today expressed its understanding at having to leave
Beijing's famed imperial-era Beihai Park.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jianzhong, a spokesman for the corporation, said here
that it is a normal business procedure for the Beijing Municipal
Administration of Parks and Gardens to discontinue the company's
contract to operate in the park when it expires in 2002, saying, "
We have no doubt about that."
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Administration of Parks and Gardens
recently decided in order to maintain the integrated imperial
style of Beihai Park, the fast food restaurant should move from
the park when its seven-year contract runs out.
</P>
<P>
This decision is based on a proposal by the Beijing Municipal
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference.
</P>
<P>
An official of the administration said that in the future, no
foreign fast food restaurants will be permitted to operate in the
city's imperial-era parks, because their presence clashes with the
classic environment.
</P>
<P>
A taxi driver named Liu said that the government's decision is
right, suggesting that all those buildings not fit for these
imperial parks should be removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
