<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes U.S., British Allegations Over Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi military spokesman on
Thursday refuted allegations made by the U.S. and Britain that they
bombed only military targets Tuesday in the no-fly zones in
southern and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the spokesman said that facts have proved that
the U.S. and British warplanes on Tuesday bombed civilian
facilities such as villages and filling stations, resulting in the
death of a driver who was driving a water-carrying truck.
</P>
<P>
The truck driver, identified as Tahsein Hussein Mohammad, was
killed Tuesday when the U.S. and British planes bombed two
villages, Al-Erbeid and Abu Nashka, in addition to the Al-Eidan
filling station in the northern Neiveva province.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the continued aggressions of the U.S.
and Britain will not suppress the Iraqi people's will of
steadfastness to challenge the aggressors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long claimed the U.S. and British planes patrol and
bomb civilian and service facilities in the two so-called no-fly
zones.
</P>
<P>
A total of 295 civilians have been killed and 860 others injured
in the regular bombings of the U.S. and British planes on Iraq
since December 1998, said Iraq in letters to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and president of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have maintained that their planes bomb only
military targets in the no-fly zones and have been trying to
minimize the potential for collateral damage and risk to civilians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British aircraft use bases in Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait to mount their patrols of the southern no-fly zone which was
set up after the 1991 Gulf War by the U.S. and Britain with their
claimed aim of protecting the region's Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
A similar air exclusion zone, patrolled from Turkey, was imposed
over northern Iraq to protect the Kurdish community there as
claimed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
