<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chissano: Southern Africa Needs More Investments in Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries need
more investments to better its infrastructures with catastrophe-
preventing system at first, said Mozambican President Joaquim
Alberto Chissano in Berlin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chissano attended the "African Economy Forum 2000" here,
leading delegates from 12 Southern African Development Community(
SADC) countries.
</P>
<P>
The African delegation included Botswana President Festus G.
Mogae, Lesotho Prime Minister Mosisili, Mauritius Prime Minister
Ramgoolam, King Maswati III of Swaziland, as well as ministers
from Angola, Malawi, Namibia, South Africa, Tanzania, Zambia, and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said the most devastating flood in his country last
month had killed 700 people and affected over 2 million.
</P>
<P>
"The damages were by far extensive because the country lack a
viable system of prevention," he said, adding that Mozambique had
planned to build a few dams to prevent floods but was unable to
proceed while lack of financial resources.
</P>
<P>
In less favored countries such as Namibia and Botswana the
loss will be more huge if they are hit by floods, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano urged more western investment into the region's
infrastructure, including transport, communication, energy and
water, to help creating sustainable environment.
</P>
<P>
Although SADC countries have made progress in their macro
economic reforms and their finance are healthy, foreign
investments in the region remain in low level especially compared
with Asia and Latin America, said Chissano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
