<HEADLINE> More Russia-Peru Trade Foreseen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian ambassador to Peru Valentin
Bogomasov said Thursday that the election of Vladimir Putin as
president of Russia promises more trade between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat said that bilateral relation with Peru
will intensify because Putin's presidency represents the
continuity of the policy of promotion of trade relations with
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Peru is seen by Russia as an strategic partner for its
geographical location and of great importance for the increase of
Russian exports and imports to and from the region, according to
Bogomasov.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian businessmen are interested in buying fish meal,
seafood, cotton, handicrafts, and Peruvian textile products.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian-Russian trade exchanges amount to 60 million U.S.
dollars, of which 35 million dollars give Russia an edge, although
there is a positive trend in the increase of Peruvian exports to
that country.
</P>
<P>
Bogomasov said that the visit of Peruvian Fishing Minister
Cesar Luna Victoria is being prepared to let him know the
potential of the exports of fish meal to Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
