<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia's Accession to NATO Possible: NATO Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Georgia may join the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in the future, said a high-
ranking NATO official in Georgian capital of Tbilisi on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NATO regards Georgia as an important partner, and it is very
important for NATO to maintain stability in the Caucasian region
where Georgia plays a major role, chairman of the NATO Military
Committee Admiral Guido Venturoni told a news briefing at the
Georgian Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and he Wednesday
discussed bilateral cooperation under NATO's Partnership for Peace
program and the possibility of Tbilisi's joining the North
Atlantic Alliance. The sides agreed that Georgia's accession to
NATO would take time.
</P>
<P>
Venturoni arrived in Tbilisi on Wednesday for a three-day visit.
He said the goal of his visit is to support Georgia's involvement
in NATO's Partnership for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
Georgia joined the program in March 1994, since then the
political and military relations between the former soviet
republic and NATO have developed fast.
</P>
<P>
According to the Georgian Defense Ministry, the two sides have
planned nearly 200 joint events in 2000. Georgia has taken part in
NATO's military exercises for nine times. The sides will conduct
more maneuvers on Georgia's territory in the framework of NATO's
Partnership for Peace program this year and in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Georgian defense Minister David Tevsadze told the press that
the visit by the chief NATO military official is very important
for Tbilisi and various questions will be mulled over, in
particular,including the organization of NATO international
military exercises in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
This year Georgia intends to host exercises in which Georgia, U.
S.,Azerbaijan and possibly Armenia will participate, while other
large-scale NATO military exercises are also planned for 2001 in
West Georgia, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Shevardnadze has repeatedly said that Georgia plans
to"knock on NATO's door by 2005" when his second mandate as state
of head ends.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Georgia and Russia held talks in Moscow over the
withdrawal of about 10,000 Russian army servicemen currently
deployed in Georgia. Tbilisi demanded Moscow close all its
military bases in Georgia in three years, the latter agreed to
pull out its units by steps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
