<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Praises Foreign Armed Forces for Aid in Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi Thursday met with representatives of the foreign armed
forces involved in rescue operations in the country during the
February-March flooding to thank them for their work.
</P>
<P>
He told the representatives from South Africa, Malawi, Britain,
Libya, the United States, Spain, the Netherlands and Portugal that
"although previously we did not know each other, all of us,
civilian and military, worked together in good coordination and
harmony and united in the same objective of saving Mozambican
lives."
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi said that in the three weeks of the joint rescue
operation in March, about 26,400 people were saved from the
waters.
</P>
<P>
The foreign military teams also transported 9,430 tons of
humanitarian aid and distributed about 3.5 million litres of clean
drinking, he said.
</P>
<P>
He observed that military medic staff, particularly from Spain,
were also involved. They treated about 6,000 patients and carried
out 43 surgical operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the foreign military aircraft
had been flying for over 5,000 hours, and the costs of this are
estimated at 25 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi recognized that for any government, "it is not easy to
send its armed forces to other countries, even for humanitarian
missions. The missions are risky and they involve high logistical
and financial costs."
</P>
<P>
He told the representatives that the Mozambican government was
very pleased "at the massive public support in your countries for
your mission in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"So apart from your armies, you represent the solidarity of
your peoples with the Mozambique people," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the lessons learned from this operation could be
used to help Mozambique and the entire southern African region
face future disasters effectively.
</P>
<P>
This involved the capacity building of Mozambique's own defense
force, the FADM (forca armada de defensa mozanbicana), which
should have a key role to play whenever disasters strike, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi expressed the hope that those present at the meeting
would help Mozambique develop its armed forces "so as to make them
a powerful instrument for saving people who fall victim to natural
disasters."
</P>
<P>
"It is our desire to acquire the necessary capacity so that we
can take part in humanitarian missions in other countries, just as
your armies did in Mozambique," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Defense Minister Tobias Dai, in the first phase of
the disaster in February before the foreign military teams
arrived, the FADM had just one helicopter and two light planes for
rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
With these few resources, the Mozambican military rescued
17,612 people, transported 101 tons of cargo and removed 55
corpses, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0030 </DOCNO>
