<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Trade, Industry Make Headway: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Trade and Industry
Minister Kassahun Ayele said here Thursday that the removal of
bureaucratic red tape, efficient issuance of trade licenses and
revisions of tariff and trade policies have brought considerable
benefit to the country's business community.
</P>
<P>
He told mass media that a great deal has also been done to
enhance the capacity of the country's trade and industry
especially by providing training, consultancy and other services
for the business community.
</P>
<P>
The number of importers and exporters which stood at 3,419 five
years ago has shot up to 8,469 at present, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the number of medium and big
industrial establishments in Ethiopia has risen from 501 in 1995
to well over 760 at present.
</P>
<P>
He noted that food and beverage production, tobacco, textiles,
leather, woodworks, printing, chemicals and metal works were the
major industrial projects launched during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The government is planning to increase industrial income by
strengthening the existing leather and textile factories and by
enhancing the competitiveness of industries in general, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
