<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 3 Tons of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's security forces seized about
three tons of various narcotic drugs last week in the eastern
Kerman Province, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The drugs were seized from passing vehicles and during an armed
clash with the drug traffickers in northern and southern parts of
the province, said Brigadier General Abbasali Rouhi, provincial
commander of the security forces.
</P>
<P>
A number of vehicles and motorbikes were among the confiscated
items, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a main transit route for drugs smuggled from neighboring
Pakistan and Afghanistan, the world's largest opium producer, to
Europe and oil-rich Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
It started strict anti-drug campaigns in 1989 after the Iranian
Majlis, or parliament, passed an anti-drug law authorizing capital
punishment for drug traffickers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Should Withdraw Completely From Lebanon: U. N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel should pull its troops
completely out of south Lebanon in the planned withdrawal this
July, U.N. Middle East Special Envoy Terje Larsen stressed here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Thursday
afternoon, the visiting envoy said that the pullback should be
implemented to the 1923 international border between Israel and
Lebanon, with no Israeli positions remaining in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Larsen also confirmed that a team of senior advisors and legal
experts accompanying with him would try to finalize the issue of
the redeployment line with Israeli defense establishment officials
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The envoy, dispatched by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
arrived in Israel earlier in the day to begin his "fact-finding
tour" to the Middle East region, lasting from April 27 to May 9.
</P>
<P>
Focusing his works on ensuring a quiet Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon, he is also due to visit Lebanon and a number of relevant
countries in the region, including Syria, Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is scheduled to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Thursday evening to discuss all these issues regarding the
withdrawal, such as the redeployment line, the presence of U.N.
peacekeeping forces in areas evacuated by Israel, and the exact
pullback timetable.
</P>
<P>
On March 5, Israeli cabinet agreed to withdraw Israel Defense
Forces (IDF) from the so-called security zone in south Lebanon,
which was set up by Israel in 1985 to prevent cross-border
guerrilla attacks against its north, by July as Barak had pledged.
</P>
<P>
Since then, some military experts were worrying of the possible
escalating Lebanese guerrillas' dangerous infiltration into Israeli
settlements along the international border after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
In a pullback plan prepared by IDF General Staff Lt.Gen. Shaul
Mofaz, code-named "Morning Twilight", Israeli troops will withdraw
to the borderline before its invasion into Lebanon in 1978, leaving
some large outposts in Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
However, most Israeli politicians, including Barak, believed
such a withdrawal should be wrapped in international legitimacy
under the U.N. Security Council Resolutions 425 and 426 to leave
the responsibility for keeping peace along the border on the
shoulders of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The two resolutions, passed in 1978, call for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli pullout from all Lebanese territories and a
return of full sovereignty to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Levy sent a letter to Annan on April 17 to formally notify the
U.N. that it would complete the withdrawal from Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
Israel officials are garnering Annan's support in the past weeks
for extending the mandate of the current U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) to the whole security zone to fill the security
vacuum left by the departing IDF.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong peacekeeping troops, established in 1978 on the
basis of Resolution 425 from nine countries, are currently deployed
primarily in the western and central sectors of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the outbreak of the 1982 Lebanon War, UNIFIL was
authorized to expand to 7,000 personnel. Although this was never
implemented, some legal experts had argued that the precedent could
be used to meet future requirements.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is expected to meet with senior officers of the UNIFIL in
Jerusalem to define the possible expansion of the U.N. peacekeeping
mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
