<HEADLINE> U.S. Provides 83 Million Dollars in Grants to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 27 (Xinhua)-- The United States has agreed to
provide 83 million U.S. dollars in grants to Jordan to help the
kingdom build and innovate water projects and improve the
management system in the water sector.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the grants was signed here on Thursday by
Jordan's Minister of Trade, Industry and Supply Mohammed Halayka
and U.S. Ambassador to Amman William Burns on behalf of their
governments.
</P>
<P>
The grant was the first portion of an overall U.S. economic
assistance package for the kingdom in the year 2000, which is
expected to total 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the U.S. government will provide 83 million
dollars to develop and implement urgently-needed water projects in
the southern harbor city Aqaba, Amman and other big cities.
</P>
<P>
Amman itself reported a yearly shortage of 250 million cubic
meters of fresh water and water leakage remained largely unchecked
in the capital city due to its ageing pipe system and poor
management.
</P>
<P>
The new grant was also part of an on-going five-year and 400-
million-dollar U.S. aid package to the kingdom, which was launched
in 1997, to improve management and facilities in the water sector.
</P>
<P>
Washington takes Jordan as an ally in the Arab world after it
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, the second Arab country
after Egypt to strike such a peace deal with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
It has been steadily increasing its economic and financial
assistances to the kingdom in recent years to award its role as a
major peace broker between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government provided some 300 million dollars in various
economic and military aid packages to the kingdom in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
