<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Appoints New Deputy Chief of Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Major General Moshe Ya'alon,
Commander of Israel's Central Command, had been promoted to Deputy
Chief of General Staff, Israel Defense Forces spokesman announced
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ya'alon will replace his predecessor Major General Uzi Dayan in
the next few months, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Dayan, also a former central commander, was once considered as
the most promising candidate to succeed the current Chief of
General Staff Shaul Mofaz after the Lieutenant General's term ends
in July 2001.
</P>
<P>
Dayan is a relative of Moshe Dayan, one of Israel's founding
fathers and a military legend.
</P>
<P>
He has been serving in his current position since July 1998 and
is expected to finish his three-year term in September. According
to the IDF tradition, the popular general should be given another
term before his possible promotion.
</P>
<P>
However, Mofaz managed to persuade Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak earlier in the month to adopt his plan to explore more
candidates as his successors.
</P>
<P>
In the plan, Mofaz would switch deputies in his midterm to
ensure that there will be more than one name to be placed on the
table of decision-maker to decide his replacement.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mofaz and Dayan had a chilly relationship,
which was the real drive behind Mofaz's proposal.
</P>
<P>
However, Mofaz denied the report by saying "My considerations
regarding the replacement of Uzi Dayan are totally free of any
personal considerations and are completely pertinent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
