<HEADLINE> Black Sea States Discuss Anti-Pollution Cooperation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Black Sea and
Danube Commission began a two-day meeting in Istanbul, Turkey, on
Thursday to further their anti-pollution cooperation, reported
the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of Turkey, Russia, Ukraine, Bulgaria, Romania
and Georgia attended the meeting which is being held within the
framework of the Bucharest Agreement signed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Fugen Ok, Chairperson of the commission and an official of the
Turkish Foreign Ministry, urged an agreement on setting up a
permanent secretariat to make sure that the Bucharest Agreement is
fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
She said that Turkey wants the secretariat to be based in
Istanbul or in a Russian city if other countries prefer it.
</P>
<P>
Ok also asked the participants to seek ways to raise anti-
pollution funds to meet the demand of the projects required under
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Littoral states of the Black Sea have in recent years made big
efforts in order to achieve wide-ranging cooperation in the fields
of sea traffic control, safety of passage, environmental pollution
monitoring, search and rescue, humanitarian assistance and the
monitoring and protecting of fishing fleets.
</P>
<P>
Naval Commanders of the six Black Sea nations met in Ankara last
Thursday in search of military cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the Istanbul meeting of the Black Sea and Danube
Commission on Friday, Turkey will hand over the commission
chairmanship to Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
