<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Request to Delay Lockerbie Trial Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A Scottish judge on Thursday
rejected a request from prosecution to postpone the trial of two
Libyan suspects for the 1988 Lockerbie airliner bombing.
</P>
<P>
Presiding Judge Lord Ranald Sutherland said: "I am not
satisfied that a postponement is necessary."
</P>
<P>
"I should feel obliged to refuse the request," he added.
</P>
<P>
The judge based his decision on the fact that the accused had
already been in custody for 416 days, an unprecedented length of
time under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution now has 48 hours to appeal against the refusal.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors had sought a delay to the scheduled start on May 3
of the long-awaited trial, because of surprise defense plans to
produce 119 witnesses from a range of countries. Prosecutors had
wanted the trial to be delayed until June 28.
</P>
<P>
The ruling by the Scottish judge followed two delays since
Libya extradited the defendants on April 5, 1999, to face charges
in the mid-air bombing. Each of those delays was at the request
of the defense.
</P>
<P>
Sutherland agreed last December to postpone the trial by three
months to May after the defense said it needed more time because
of the huge amount of evidence and witnesses involved.
</P>
<P>
At a pre-trial hearing, lawyers for Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and
Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima revealed plans to try to prove that others
were involved in the bombing of a Boeing 747 airliner over the
Scottish village of Lockerbie on December 21 of 1988, killing 259
aboard and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
A three-year investigation concluded to obtain a warrant for
the arrest of the two Libyan suspects, both staff of the Libyan
Arab Airlines in Malta in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The hearing was at Camp Zeist, a former United States military
base ceded to Britain by the Netherlands for the trial.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal brokered by the United Nations last year, Libya
handed over the two men to stand trial in the Netherlands under
Scottish law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
