<HEADLINE> Gene-based Pharmaceuticals Promise Immortality Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Two of Canada's largest drug
companies are working toward "virtual immortality to coming
generations" and urging governments to assess how well therapies
work to contain costs and maximize benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail newspaper reported Thursday that the Tronto-
based Glaxo Wellcome Inc. and the Montreal-based Merck Frosst
Canada &AMP; Co. hold the promise that future generations could live
for 200 years with the development of drugs that are designed to
prevent illness and aging.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Glaxo's vice-president Michael Levy as
saying advances in genetics will soon allow pharmaceutical
companies to develop such drugs.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, designer drugs could be tailored to specific
individuals based on their genetic makeup.
</P>
<P>
Companies such as Glaxo are already working on the development
of identity cards that would contain a person's genetic code and
its medical implications, he said.
</P>
<P>
But with the development of the new drugs, there will arise
complex ethical, legal and social issues, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Among those issues is how society will pay for the enormously
expensive task of developing such genetically based
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
The brand-name drug companies are expected to invest 1 billion
Canadian dollars (about 678 million U.S. dollars) in medical
research this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
