<HEADLINE> France to Strengthen Teaching of Literature in High Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The French government has decided
to strengthen the teaching of literature in public high schools by
increasing classes of French, literature, history, foreign
languages, and ancient languages like Latin and Greek.
</P>
<P>
Presenting a package of reform proposals for schools, the new
Minister of National Education Jack Lang said on Thursday that he
wants to give ``an attractive character'' to the literature
classes which have been losing its importance in the schools for
years.
</P>
<P>
The obligatory hours for attending classes of French will be
increased from five to six hours each week, while that for
literature will be added to four hours instead of 2.5 hours and
foreign language class given an extra hour.
</P>
<P>
Students can also have two alternative hours of class for Latin
and Greek each week.
</P>
<P>
Lang, who is a former minister of culture, replaced technocrat
Claude Allegre as minister of national education one month ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
