<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Rejects Accusations Against Its Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States software
company Microsoft on Thursday dismissed suggestions that its
Windows 2000 operating system has broken the European Union's
competition rules.
</P>
<P>
The company, already facing the threat of being split up in two
after anti-trust problems in the United States, was responding to
an investigation by the European Commission, the executive body of
the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The commission is investigating whether the software could give
the American company a stranglehold over server software and
ultimately electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
John Frank, Microsoft's senior director for European law and
corporate affairs, told the press on Thursday that Microsoft's
competitors had complained just before the launch of Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
The commission launched in February a probe into Windows 2000
after complaints that Microsoft had designed parts of the new
operating system in a way which would allow it to extend its
dominance in personal computer operating systems to server
operating systems and ultimately electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
Mario Monti, European Union commissioner for competition, said
that the new operating system is designed "in a way which permits
only Microsoft products to be fully interoperable".
</P>
<P>
If the allegations against the American software company were
proven, the commission could force the company to make changes to
Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under EU rules, if a company refuses to come into line it could
face fines of up to 10 percent of its worldwide revenues though
such a fine has never been levied before.
</P>
<P>
A United States judge ruled on April 3 that Microsoft had
violated the U.S. anti-trust laws by abusing a monopoly it held in
personal computer operating systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
