<HEADLINE> Netherlands Urges Internet Use by Schools, Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands on Thursday
kicked off an assortment of measures aimed at drawing students and
small businesses to the Internet and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
A total of 710 million U.S. dollars will be spent on 12,000
Dutch schools to encourage the use of computer network services.
</P>
<P>
"We have moved up from the 23rd place to eighth for Internet
education," said Dutch Education Minister Loek Hermans. "But we
need to be number one."
</P>
<P>
The Dutch government is also spending 2.9 million dollars on
launching an e-commerce awareness campaign among small and medium-
sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Dutch newspapers, radio and television advertisements will urge
firms to embrace business-to-business or B2B e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Government authorities said that only one in five small and
medium-sized enterprises in the country now sells their products
and services via the computer network, with a further 14 percent
saying that they have planned to do so.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of information technology is enormous," said
Dutch Economy Minister Annemarie Jorrtsma. "But we are not all
taking advantage of them. If we compare ourselves with Sweden and
Finland we have some ground to make up."
</P>
<P>
The education and awareness-raising campaign will also cover
such areas as justice and transport. The campaign is called"
Netherlands goes digital". 
</P>
</TEXT>
