<HEADLINE> UNICEF Calls for Debt Forgiveness for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) on Thursday called on the world's donor
countries to forgive immediately the debt of poor countries that
have a viable plan for achieving the goal of education for all.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the World Education Forum in Dakar, Senegal, Carol
Bellamy, Executive Director of UNICEF, urged delegates and the
international community to accelerate efforts to ensure that
education plans and programs receive adequate support.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said the efforts can only succeed with the active
support of all sectors of society -- families and communities,
governments and funding agencies, service providers of all sectors,
the media, the private sector and civil society.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Bellamy urged the Forum to try to ensure that
all children are in school by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy urged that five key areas be embraced by the 1,500
participants of the Forum: enrich early child care and learning,
reach excluded children, enhance girls' education, improve
education quality and restore education in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The Forum is the largest meeting on education since the 1990
World Conference on education for All, which aimed to achieve
education for all by 2000. The Dakar meeting is expected to reset
the target of quality basic education for all children to the year
2015 and to end disparities between girls and boys in school by
2005.  
</P>
</TEXT>
