<HEADLINE> NATO Needs New Strategy to Employ Force: Clark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The western military alliance
needs a new strategy for using force in future crisis environment,
said Wesley Clark on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. army general, speaking at his final press conference
before handing over May 3 to U.S. air force general Joseph Ralston
the NATO command in Europe, said: "We need a new strategy where
there is better appreciation for the proper way to employ force in
the post-Cold War environment."
</P>
<P>
"Once the threshold is crossed to employ force, then force
should be employed as rapidly and decisively as possible," the
outgoing general added.
</P>
<P>
NATO began bombing the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia last
March 24 in the hope that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
would soon concede to international demands but the air campaign
lasted 78 days though with radical reinforcements from the 19-
nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The general said that the Balkans where NATO has got almost 70,
000 troops on the ground as peacekeepers would remain the main
challenge for his successor as it had been for him.
</P>
<P>
But the American admitted that the military mission would only
succeed unless the international effort on the political front is
a success.
</P>
<P>
"I think that will remain the principal challenge for the(NATO)
headquarters," Clark said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
