A Downing Street spokesman said Thursday that the talks will be
held on next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Ahern will hold separate meetings with members of
Sinn Fein, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), the largest Protestant
party in the British province, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland peace accord reached in 1998 came into
jeopardy in February when Britain suspended the province's
Protestant-Catholic coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Britain took the action on the grounds that the Irish
Republican Army had failed to disarm.
</P>
<P>
Both London and Dublin are now cautiously confident that they
can revive peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This is a continuation of the discussions begun before Easter
on how we can move the peace process forward. There was the
understanding there would be an intensification after Easter,"
Blair's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Blair flew to Northern Ireland last week to meet Northern
Ireland politicians and then travelled on to Dublin to see Ahern.
</P>
<P>
The two men met in London again last Thursday in a signal they
intend to launch a new push to seal lasting peace in the province.
</P>
