<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Needs 310 Million U.S. Dollars to Build Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has not
yet raised the 310 million U.S. dollars required to rebuild the
Sena railway line that runs from the port of Beira to Malawi and
to the coal mines of Moatize in the western Province of Tete.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Thursday in the Mozambican parliament, the Assembly
of the Republic, Deputy Transport Minister Antonio Fernando said
that although there was a general agreement that the Sena line is
vital to economy of central Mozambique, nothing could be done
until the funds have been mobilized.
</P>
<P>
Fernando, who was speaking during the debate on the
government's budget and plan for this year, pointed out that it
was not a question of rehabilitating the line, but of completely
rebuilding it "because the line no longer exists, it's just bush."
</P>
<P>
The line was comprehensively sabotaged by the apartheid-backed
Renamo (a Resistencia Nacional de Mozambique) rebels in the early
1980s, with the rails torn up, stations burnt to the ground and
rolling stock destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Only when the Sena line is rebuilt will there be possible
export of significant quantities of Moatize coal, Fernando said.
The line is also of key importance for taking agricultural
products from the Zambezi valley to port, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy minister, 210 million U.S. dollars is
the cost of rebuilding the line, and a further 100 million U.S.
dollars is needed to buy new locomotives.
</P>
<P>
The total projected income from Mozambican commodity exports
this year is 296 million U.S. dollars. "Even if we used all of
that, it's not enough to rebuild the Sena line," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is looking for partners for BOT
(Build-Operate-Transfer) scheme for this railway. Under this
arrangement, the private investors would rebuild the line, operate
it for a specific period to recoup their costs and make profits,
and then hand it over to the government.
</P>
<P>
"We are in intensive negotiations with China and Canada for the
 financial engineering required," said Fernando.
</P>
<P>
A second problem railway is the branch line from Cuamba to
Lichinga in the northernmost Province of Niassa. This line should
be the most economic means of supplying fuel and other basic goods
to Lichinga and all the central and northern districts of Niassa.
</P>
<P>
A full rehabilitation of the Lichinga line would cost 126
million U.S. dollars. This sum of money is not available yet, but
the publicly owned rail company, CFM (Companhia Ferroviaria de
Mozambique), is planning to spend 8 million U.S. dollars by April
2001 in replacing the sleepers, and making the line somewhat
safer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
