<HEADLINE> Five Countries Aim to Establish Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka,
Myanmar and Thailand agreed here on Thursday to work toward a Free
Trade Agreement among them, which they hope would help enhance
trade and investment cooperation in the region and finally lead to
a Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
The five nations reached consensus during the second
ministerial meeting of the BIMST-EC (Bangladesh, India, Myanmar,
Sri Lanka, Thailand - Economic Cooperation) here, which also
decided to form an inter-governmental group consisting of trade
officials to prepare a concept paper on possible approaches toward
the establishment of the proposed Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
"The move to establish a Free Trade Area in the region was in
line with the shared vision of prosperity through enhanced trade
and economic cooperation," said Indian Commerce and Industry
Minister Murasoli Maran, adding that the concept paper is expected
to be readied within six months.
</P>
<P>
The initiative would also act as a bridge linking India to
ASEAN, Maran noted.
</P>
<P>
It was also decided at the BIMST-EC meeting that the member
nations would move ahead with a proposal to establish proper
transport linkages between them through a project to be called "
Southern Corridors of the Trans-Asian Railways and Asian Highways
Projects." 
</P>
</TEXT>
