<HEADLINE> India Rules Out Third Party Mediation in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- India Thursday ruled out any
third party mediation in the Kashmir issue whether as "facilitator,
mediator or in the form of intervention."
</P>
<P>
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh told the upper house of
parliament: "I want to make it clear there can be no third party
intervention in Kashmir by any means either as facilitator,
mediator or in the form of intervention."
</P>
<P>
He indicated that Kashmir was not the core issue between India
and Pakistan, and instead, "Kashmir is at the core of Indian
nationhood."
</P>
<P>
He also accused Pakistan of interrupting the peace process and
said it was for Islamabad to recreate the condition for resumption
of dialogue with India.
</P>
<P>
"We have no ill-will or enmity towards the people of Pakistan.
We were the initiators of the dialogue which was interrupted by
Pakistan and the onus is now on Islamabad to restore the right
condition for talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Singh said his government was re-assessing the situation after
Kargil, Kandahar and the military coup in Pakistan. 
</P>
