<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Rural Development Loan to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Manila-based Asian Development
Bank (ADB) approved Thursday a 20-million-U.S.-dollar project to
Cambodia to give the country's rural households better access to
rural finance.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said the Rural Credit and Savings Project will
contribute to poverty reduction through the provision of income-
generating activities and sustainable savings facilities for
households in the rural areas, where about 90 percent of the poor
live.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a press release that the loan will be used to
establish a revolving fund in the country's Rural Development Bank,
a wholesale banking institution, which will channel funds through
microfinance institutions to their subborrowers.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan has a maturity of 32 years, including a grace
period of 8 years. The interest charge will be one percent per
annum during the grace period and 1.5 percent per annum thereafter.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also decided on Thursday to grant 2.9 million dollars
to assist the Pakistani government in strengthening its
institutional capacity for judicial and legal reform to increase
efficiency in the system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
