<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy Rises 5.4 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy, driven by
the biggest jump in consumer spending in nearly 17 years, grew at
an annual rate of 5.4 percent in the first quarter of 2000, the
Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the gross domestic product (GDP), the total
output of goods and services in the country, was slightly slower
than the breakneck 7.3 percent rate posted in the fourth quarter
of 1999, the strongest showing in nearly 16 years.
</P>
<P>
First-quarter growth was led by a whopping 8.3 percent rate of
increase in consumer spending, the largest gain since a 8.6
percent rate posted in the second quarter of 1983.The consumer
spending increased 5.9 percent in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve, fearing that unchecked growth could worsen
inflation, has raised interest rates five times since June 30 to
slow the speeding economy. Given the outlook for continued strong
growth, many economists believe the Fed policy makers will boost
interest rates once again when they meet on May 16.
</P>
<P>
An inflation gauge tied to GDP that is closely watched by Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan rose at an annual rate of 3.2 percent in
the first quarter, the largest increase since a 3.5 percent rate
in the third quarter of 1994. The inflation measure rose at a 2.5
percent rate in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Americans' spending spree pulled the nation's savings rate,
savings as a percentage of disposable income, to a record
quarterly low of 0.7 percent, down from the previous all-time low
of 1.8 percent recorded in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Businesses, confident that consumers will continue spending,
boosted their investment in new equipment and plants in the first
quarter by a sizzling rate of 21.2 percent, up from a 2.9 percent
rate in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
That 21.2 percent rate marked the largest increase since the
first quarter of 1998 and was another major factor adding to the
overall economy's growth in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to first-quarter growth was spending by state
and local governments which grew at a 7.4 percent rate in the
first quarter, up from a 6.4 percent rate in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit, however, continued to be a drag on
economic growth. Imports rose at a rate of 9.5 percent in the
first quarter, up from a 8.7 percent rate. Exports fell at a 0.2
percent rate, compared to a 10.1 percent increase in fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses increased inventories of 31.1 billion U.S.
dollars in the first quarter, following increased of 66.7 billion
dollars in the fourth quarter. The change subtracted 1.39
percentage points from the first-quarter change in real GDP, after
adding 1.24 percentage points to the fourth-quarter change.
</P>
<P>
Real federal government consumption expenditures and gross
investment decreased 15.5 percent last quarter, in contrast to an
increase of 14.7 percent in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
All the changes show the economy growing at an annual rate of
119.4 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter, pushing the
country's GDP to 9.2 trillion dollars, after adjusting for
inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECB Raises Rates by Quarter Percentage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECD)
Thursday raised its three leading interests rates by 0.25-
percentage point amid record weak euro.
</P>
<P>
The ECB governing council made the decision at its routine
meeting in Frankfurt, warning against "upside risks to price
stability" in the euro region and the present exchange rate of the
euro.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the ECB said its main refinancing rate
would be set at 3.75 percent, the marginal lending facility rate
at 4.75 per cent, and the deposit facility rate, 2.75 percent,
after this Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The governing council expressed concern about upside risks to
price stability which arise from strong growth in monetary and
credit aggregates, as well as from the present level of the
exchange rate of the euro," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The weak exchange rate does not reflect the booming economy in
the euro zone, the ECB stressed
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the exchange rate of euro hit its record low
of 0.9139 U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming this move as "absolutely right," the German
business did not expect the euro to be stronger until this summer.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is absolutely right and well-grounded," said
Norbert Walter, chief economist of Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
 But the common currency of 11 European countries will stay
weak until this summer since "no positive impulse is expected," he
said, adding that the low exchange rate against U.S.dollar would
not hurt the "internal stability" of euro.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Association of German Industry said, euro would
become stronger only after the euro nations pass their "reform jam.
"
</P>
<P>
"Not the ECB, but the economic policy of the euro states
should be responsible for the weak currency," the powerful
organization said in a statement. 
</P>
