<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wages, Benefits Rise 4.3 Percent in 12 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Americans' wages and benefits
increased 4.3 percent in the 12 months ending in March, the
fastest growth in pay in eight years, the Labor Department said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the Labor Department's Employment Cost Index
was the biggest 12-month advance since a 4.3 percent increase in
December 1991. In the 12 months ending in December, wages and
benefits rose by a more moderate 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
While higher wages and benefits are good news for workers,
economists are concerned that if companies pass on rising labor
costs to buyers of their products, it could trigger higher
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has already raised interest rates five
times since June in an effort to slow the booming economy to a
more sustainable growth rate and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
The boost in pay pressures reflected a 4 percent increase in
wages and salaries and a 5 percent rise in benefit costs, items
such as health insurance and pensions.
</P>
<P>
For just the January-March quarter, wages and benefits rose by
1.4 percent, the biggest quarterly increase in more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The Employment Cost Index is closely watched for signals it can
provide about underlying price pressures in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has been expressing
fears that the tightest labor market in three decades will
eventually spawn inflationary wage increases as employers are
forced to pay higher and higher wages to attract a dwindling
supply of workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
