<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Canada to Be Set Up in Montreal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Quebec Province will soon
set up an electronic stock exchange in Montreal which is expected
to compete directly with other Canadian stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Under a recent deal with Nasdaq, the system known as Nasdaq
Canada will be set up and running in Montreal by June.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Premier Lucien Bourchard, who announced the deal in New
York on Wednesday, has said the provincial National Assembly will
pass legislation within the week.
</P>
<P>
Lucien described the deal as a "major initiative that will mark
the history of the development of Quebec's and Canada's financial
market."
</P>
<P>
In the first phase of the agreement, all interlisted stocks
will trade in U.S. dollars and any initial public offerings will
have to conform to U.S. regulations.
</P>
<P>
The second phase set for early next year will see the
establishment of a Canadian market on the Nasdaq trading platform.
</P>
