<HEADLINE> Iran's Judiciary Closes Two More Reformist Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary on
Thursday closed down two more reformist papers, Sobh-e Emruz and
Mosharekat, bringing the total number of periodicals suspended to
17.
</P>
<P>
Sobh-e Emruz (This Morning) is published by Saeed Hajjarian, a
prominent reformer who was shot and seriously wounded in an
assassination attempt last month, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mosharekat (Participation) is published by Mohammed Reza
Khatami, brother of President Mohammed Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Both the publishers belong to the major reformist party the
Islamic Iran Participation Front, which led reformers in the
country to an overwhelming victory in the parliamentary election in
February. 
