<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Judiciary Closes Two More Reformist Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary on
Thursday closed down two more reformist papers, Sobh-e Emruz and
Mosharekat, bringing the total number of papers and periodicals
suspended to 16.
</P>
<P>
Sobh-e Emruz (This Morning) is published by Saeed Hajjarian, a
prominent reformer who was shot and seriously wounded in an
assassination attempt last month, the Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary had ordered the closure of the daily on Monday,
but revoked the order later, citing Hajjarian's hospitalization as
the reason.
</P>
<P>
Mosharekat (Participation) is run by Mohammed Reza Khatami,
brother of pro-reform President Mohammed Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Both reformers are leaders of the major reformist party the
Islamic Iran Participation Front (IIPF), which led reformers in the
country to an overwhelming victory in the parliamentary election in
February, bringing an end to the long time domination of the
conservatives in the legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Two separate statements made by the Justice Department of Tehran
on Thursday said the two dailies had been informed to stop
publication due to violation of the press law, IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
This brings to 16 the total number of dailies and periodicals
closed down by the judiciary in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
The Mosharekat daily had received a warning from the
conservative press court on Tuesday for reprinting and changing its
looks after other reformist papers were closed.
</P>
<P>
"If the paper fails to pay attention to the legal note of the
court, proper decision would be taken against it," press court
judge Saeed Mortazavi warned in a letter sent to Mohammad Reza
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary's move was part of the stepped-up effort of the
conservatives, who are the real rulers of the Islamic country, to
curb the reformist campaign which has been growing since President
Mohammed Khatami took office in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Appoints Negotiator for Hostages Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that it has appointed a negotiator for the safe release
of some 20 people kidnapped from Sabah, Malaysia on Sunday and are
now believed to be in Sulu province in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao, told reporters in the Presidential Palace that President
Joseph Estrada has given him a "general and comprehensive" mandate
to negotiate with the hostage takers.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to help facilitate the safe and quick
release of these people," said Misuari.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the president has instructed the Armed Forces of
the Philippines and the Philippine National Police to fully
cooperate with him to ensure the welfare and safety of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview Thursday morning, Executive Secretary
Ronaldo Zamora said the government will not accede to any ransom
demand from the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, head of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF),
said he will consult with the Office of the President regarding
any ransom demand but added: "Offhand, I do not like to entertain
any financial demand" from the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
The MNIF, once the country's largest Muslim rebel group, signed
a peace treaty with the government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Misuari said that as part of his strategy and to ensure that
the government negotiates from a position of strength, he will
place on alert some 2,000 to 3,000 MNLF members in the area where
the hostages are held.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said the hostages seized at Sipadan island
include Malaysians, Filipinos, Germans, French and Finnish
nationals, South Africans and a Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the governments of the foreign nationals kidnapped
have agreed not to make this an international issue.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian, Finnish, and German ambassadors have
told Secretary Domingo Siazon of the Department of Foreign Affairs
that they are leaving it to the Philippine authorities to handle
the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
