<HEADLINE> No Change in India's Position on Dialogue: Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday discreetly
shrugged off India's statement on "talks about talks," saying it "
does not appear to reflect any change in India's position
prescribing conditions for dialogue with Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Pakistan's Foreign Office spokesman
Tariq Altaf in a press release issued here.
</P>
<P>
India's Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh said on Wednesday his
government would consider holding "talks about talks" with
Pakistan to avoid increasing tension between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
However, he said "the right climate" must be created for a
resumption of dialogue and Pakistan should not indulge in "endless
hostile propaganda and continuous call of Jihad (holy war)."
</P>
<P>
On the part of Pakistan, Chief Executive General Pervez
Musharraf has repeatedly expressed the hope for dialogue with
India.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Pakistan has stated its position at the
highest level," said the Foreign Office spokesman. "Pakistan is
prepared to enter into talks with India for resolution of
outstanding issues including the Kashmir issue."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan will never accept any pre-conditions for
dialogue. "We have never suggested nor will accept any conditions.
"
</P>
<P>
Official talks between the two arch-rivals in South Asia were
disrupted last May when they battled along the Line of Control in
the disputed area of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Since then India has made clear its position that it would not
resume dialogue with Pakistan until the latter stopped its support
for "Jehad" in the Indian-controlled Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
