<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Foreign Ministers to Discuss Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) foreign ministers
on peace and security opened in Zambian capital Lusaka on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will discuss how to implement the decision
by COMESA summit last year in Kenyan capital Nairobi that the
regional body should play a positive role in maintaining peace and
security, and the report adopted at this meeting will be submitted
to the COMESA summit to be held in Mauritius next month.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said in the opening speech
that peace is necessary not only for the development and
integration of COMESA, but also for Africa as a whole and the
entire world.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi summit was convinced that the economic integration
of the grouping will not be accomplished unless and until there is
durable peace and security in the sub-region. Conversely, it is
true that without sustainable development there will be no real
peace either, he said.
</P>
<P>
COMESA Secretary-General Erastus Mwencha said on the same
occasion that more than half of the COMESA member countries have
been involved in conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty, hunger, diseases and under-development that prevail
in the region are directly linked to armed conflicts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts lead to diversion of resources from economic sectors
to military expenditure, he said.
</P>
<P>
There is general consensus that the economic and political
agenda of any regional organization are two sides of the same coin
and to attain sustainable economic development requires political
stability, said Mwencha.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, established in December 1993 and headquartered in
Lusaka, is composed of 21 countries, including Angola, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo and Burundi where the civil
conflicts are raging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
