<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Police Warn Political Parties Against Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Police Commissioner
Augustine Chihuri on Thursday warned politicians against
perpetrating violence in the run up to the parliamentary elections
scheduled for May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Chihuri refuted allegations
that the police force was biased.
</P>
<P>
He said abductions of supporters of rival parties had to stop
and those who went about throwing bombs to intimidate the nation
would be brought to book and dealt with severely.
</P>
<P>
He said police would use its meagre resources to the maximum to
deal with anyone found to have participated in violence and police
had invoked sections of the Law and Order Maintenance Act to deal
with violence.
</P>
<P>
"We have concluded that political parties and their officials
were playing a big role in fueling violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said party officials made inflammatory statements which
stirred violence among supporters.
</P>
<P>
There have been 194 cases of violence and 10 deaths since
January. Seven of the deaths resulted from political violence
while three including a policeman and two white farmers were
related to farm invasions. 
</P>
