<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,181 Russian Servicemen Killed Since Chechen War Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Russian federal forces have
lost the lives of 2,181 servicemen with another 6,388 injured
since the anti-terrorist campaign in the Northern Caucasus began
on August 2, 1999, said a senior Russian officer Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The losses include 1,447 army servicemen and 734 Interior
Ministry servicemen and policemen, first deputy chief of the
Russian Armed Forces General Staff Col. Gen. Valery Manilov told
journalists.
</P>
<P>
In the breakaway republic of Chechnya, as many as 1,901
servicemen have been killed and 5,401 injured since October 1,
1999, Manilov said. Of the dead, 1,329 were army servicemen and
the rest 572 interior servicemen and policemen. Among the wounded,
3,671 were from the national army forces and 1,730 from the
Interior Ministry and the police.
</P>
<P>
He reminded that during April 20-27 a total of 37 federal
forces were killed, consisting of 32 army servicemen and five
interior servicemen and policemen, with another 63 injured: 30
army soldiers and 33 interior servicemen and policemen.
</P>
<P>
The ten Russian Interior Ministry servicemen killed in the
Serzhen-Yurt area on Wednesday are not included in the casualties,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Russian federal troops confronted another rebel ambush
Wednesday in Chechnya. At least ten servicemen, including a senior
commissioned officer, and 17 rebels were killed in the battle, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In increasing fresh clashes between Russian forces and Chechen
rebels in recent days, Russian troops' losses have kept rising
with more rebel tolls reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian units have also come under frequent rebel ambushes
lately. 15 federal servicemen lost their lives in a rebel attack
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As a counterattack, Russian forces have stepped up air raids
on rebel positions in the southern mountains of Chechnya and
strengthened the control over the province's borders with
neighboring regions.
</P>
<P>
The Russian media said hostilities in Chechnya might intensify
in the next few days. Interfax quoted sources as saying that the
purpose of the stepped-up campaign is to strip the rebels of their
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
