<HEADLINE> French Minister Regrets ECB Decision to Raise Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister Jean-
Pierre Chevenement Thursday expressed his regret about the
decision of the European Central Bank (ECB) to raise its leading
short-term interest rate.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement to the press after a cabinet meeting
chaired by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, Chevenement said it would
not help the "elan of growth" being experienced by France.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the French Minister of Economy, Finance and Industry
Laurent Fabius said that by raising interest rates, the ECB will
not help the euro, whose exchange rate with the U.S. dollar has
fallen by 20 percent over the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt-based ECB board of governors decided on Thursday
to raise its leading short-term interest rate by 0.25 percent to 3.
75 percent in order to avoid the risk of inflation in the euro
zone.
</P>
<P>
Euro immediately plunged to a new record low of one for 0.9143
dollar in the exchange market in London after the ECB announced
its decision. 
</P>
