<HEADLINE> Collection of Fairy Tales by Blind Girl Published in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A collection of more than 50
fairy tales written by a 12-year-old blind girl was published
recently in Shanghai, the first work of its kind ever created by a
blind child in China.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Liang suffered from a retinal tumor shortly after birth,
and soon after lost her sight. Fortunately, this didn't depress
her but rather stimulated her to study harder.
</P>
<P>
Yuan has learned to swim, play the piano, knit, and do other
things that sighted children are able to.
</P>
<P>
When she was very young, Yuan liked to listen to fairly tales
on the radio, inspiring her to create a number of her own fairly
tales. She is now a student at a local school for blind children.
</P>
<P>
Renowned writer Feng Yingzi has written the foreword for the
collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
