<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Drug Sales in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman with the Beijing
Municipal Public Security Bureau disclosed today that they have
uncovered the largest case yet involving the sale of some 2,313
MDMA pills, a type of amphetamine.
</P>
<P>
They captured nine members of the gang and found a total of 70,
000 yuan (8,400 U.S. dollars) in their possession.
</P>
<P>
Six caught in Beijing disclosed that they began selling MDMA at
100 yuan per pill in the city's discos and bars in March this year,
and that they got the drug in Guangzhou in south China's Guangdong
Province. With information offered by those arrested, public
security captured the other three in Guangzhou as they were
dealing the drug.
</P>
<P>
The MDMA dealer suspects confessed that they have sold more
than 30,000 MDMA pills in Beijing and other places and gained
illicit money of nearly one million yuan since January this year.
</P>
<P>
The case is still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Cunyi, deputy director of the Narcotics
Control Bureau under the Ministry of Public Security, MDMA is an
addictive substance which stimulates the nervous system, causing
drug-users to become easily excited and often to act violently.
And an overdose can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
MDMA is no longer a strange sight to young people in the discos
of Beijing, Shanghai, Nanjing, Guangzhou and Shenzhen, as it was
in 1997 when Chinese police cracked the country's first MDMA case
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Records show that the Chinese police handled 64,000 cases of
drug trafficking and production last year, 2.4 percent more than
in 1998. Some 57,000 criminal suspects, or 7.9 percent more than
in 1998, were arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
