<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK External Trade Continues Robust Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total exports and
imports continued to record robust growth last month, according to
external trade figures released Thursday by the Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports, comprising re-exports and domestic
exports, increased markedly by 26.4 percent in March over a year
earlier to 122.8 billion HK dollars (15.74 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within the total, the value of re-exports rose by 27.1 percent
to 108.2 billion HK dollars (13.87 billion U.S. dollars), and
domestic exports by 21.5 percent to 14.5 billion HK dollars (1.86
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports also increased by 25.9 percent to 136.4
billion HK dollars (17.49 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of 13.6 billion HK dollars (1.74
billion U.S. dollars), equivalent to 10 percent of the value of
imports, was recorded in March, compared with the deficit of 11.2
billion HK dollars (1.43 billion U.S. dollars) recorded a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 2000, the value of total exports
increased by 20 percent over a year earlier. Within this total,
the value of re-exports increased by 20.8 percent and domestic
exports by 14.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the first quarter of 2000 with the fourth quarter of
1999 on a seasonally adjusted basis, the value of total exports
had an increase of 6.8 percent. Within this total, the value of re-
exports and domestic exports rose by 5.9 percent and 13.3 percent
respectively. Over the same periods of comparison, the value of
imports increased by 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a government secretariat spokesman, it is for the
fifth month in a row that Hong Kong's total exports recorded a
double-digit growth, which was also the largest year-on-year
increase since January 1994.
</P>
<P>
The big exports rise was a result of broad-based rebound in
domestic demand along with the further pick-up in the economy, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
