<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Finance Minister Urges Doctors to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham
Shohat Thursday called on the doctors nationwide to return to the
negotiating table to solve their wage problems and end immediately
their strike.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry is ready for further negotiations with the
representatives of the doctors to discuss their wage increase and
any further strike by the doctors can only add more hardships to
the citizens, Shohat said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's health system was hit by a general strike Thursday,
with all public hospitals operating only on emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
The doctors and physicians at public hospitals and other health
centers nationwide have been striking for almost six weeks for wage
increase.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Medical Association (IMA) and the Physicians Union
ordered the doctors and physicians nationwide to continue their
strike Thursday after their talks with representatives of the
Finance Ministry's wages department and budgetary branch at the
beginning of the week yielded no solution.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry has so far offered an average 5 percent
annual wage increase for the doctors and physicians, but this offer
has been rejected by the IMA.
</P>
<P>
The IMA's demands include doubling the hourly salary of hospital
residents, counting duty hours at night as overtime and giving
financial incentives to medical specialists who devote all their
time to public hospital work.
</P>
<P>
It calls for changing the wage structure in which most of a
doctor's income comes from evening and weekend work and less from
work at regular hours.
</P>
<P>
The IMA also demands that public hospital doctors be given the
opportunity to work in community medical centers to increase their
income and award doctors who work in medical research and
development and do academic work.
</P>
<P>
It wants the authority to allow patients to choose their own
physicians in all public hospitals within the framework of health-
fund supplementary insurance system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
