<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Tourism Minister Erkan Mumcu and his
Palestinian counterpart Mitri Abu Eita signed a protocol for
developing the tourism cooperation between the two countries. This
was announced during the first meeting of the Turkish-Palestinian
joint economic commission held in Ankara on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The economic daily Al Alam El Yom on Thursday quoted Mumcu as
saying that about one million Turkish people are willing to visit
the tourist attractions in Palestine and the other religious
places.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Al Alam El Yom on Thursday reported that the United
States Agency for International Development is planning to grant 83
million U.S. dollars to Jordan to support its water improvement
project.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. agency also approved to grant Jordan another 46.1
million dollars to increase the economic opportunities of the
private sector and improve the investment climate in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Director of the agency in Amman, Louis Look, said the agency
plans to allocate a grant worth 200 million dollars to Jordan this
year and 250 million dollars in 2001, thus raising the total value
of U.S. aid to Jordan from 1997 to 2001 to 816 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- An energy report prepared by the Turkish Treasury
Undersecretariat, the State Planning Organization and the Minsitry
of Energy and Natural Resources said that Turkey's electricity
shortage will continuously increase in 2001 and 2002, reported the
Anatolia News Agency on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the upcoming shortage, according to the report, the
government, the Treasury and the World Bank support optimum
minimization in the number of the so-called build-operate-transfer
(BOT) projects to only three or four with firms which have a higher
chance of finding foreign financing.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank says that by giving financial guarantees to BOT
projects, the Treasury is actually exacerbating public deficits and
causing distortion in free market conditions.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has banned imports of certain chemical
substances from countries that are not party to the Chemical
Weapons Convention, reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Trade Undersecretariat announced that the decision
will take effect on April 29.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- German company Bosch opened its Bosch Common-Rail
factory in the industrial zone of Bursa, a city in western Turkey,
reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The factory will produce energy-saving diesel injection systems.
It initially planned to produce a total of 600,000 diesel injectors
this year and 3 million injectors in 2001.
</P>
<P>
President Suleyman Demirel attended the opening ceremony. Bosch
Managing Director in Turkey Klaus Peter Fouquet announced that the
waste water in the factory will be purified and reused to avoid
damaging the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
