<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke042761--Reserve Bank of India Aim to Improve Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India (RBI)
Thursday unveiled in Mumbai its Monetary and Credit Policy for the
year 2000-01, which aim to further strengthen and improve the
financial system of the country by proposing a series of
liberalization measures for the money markets and banks, the Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the PTI, the RBI has decided to progressively
implement in stages a full-fledged liquidity adjustment facility (
LAF) to be operated through repo and reverse repos in order to set
a corridor for money market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
RBI Governor Bimal Jalan, in an address to the chief executives
of scheduled commercial banks Thursday, said the LAF would help
the short term money market interest rates to move within a
corridor and impart greater stability, thus facilitating the
emergence of a short term rupee yield curve.
</P>
<P>
According to the new Monetary and Credit Policy, the use of
interest rates implied in foreign exchange forward market as a
benchmark will be permitted in addition to the existing money and
debt market rates, while the minimum maturity of certificates of
deposits will be reduced to 15 days from three months.
</P>
<P>
The policy will also allow entities to sell securities after
they have been allotted, enabling sale, settlement and transfer on
the same day, the PTI added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment-GDP Ratio Up in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment-GDP (Gross
Domestic Product) ratio in Bangladesh has shot up to over 18
percent till the end of the last fiscal year (1998-1999) from 11.5
percent in 1990-1991, according to Executive Chairman of Board of
Investment (BOI) Mokammel Haque, The New Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Domestic savings increased to 14.29 percent of GDP from 11
percent during the same period, Haque said.
</P>
<P>
Proposals for foreign direct investment (FDI) of 10.78 billion
U.S. dollars have been registered with the BOI in the last 43
months till March this year and 60 to 65 percent of the proposals
are being implemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the three years from the 1996-1997 fiscal year to the
current fiscal year (1999-2000), 4,669 projects with an estimated
investment of 9.8 billion dollars have been registered with the
BOI.
</P>
<P>
The top investors are the United States, Britain, Malaysia,
Japan, Hong Kong, Singapore, South Korea, Saudi Arabia, France,
India, Germany, Jordan, Norway and China's mainland, according to
the BOI chief.
</P>
<P>
Mokammel Haque expressed his firm belief that foreign investors
and entrepreneurs would find Bangladesh an attractive place for
industrial production, including consumer items, natural resources-
based industries and major service sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said the country enjoys the advantage under a globalized
trade and investment regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
