<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 700 Children Die of Malnutrition Daily in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Malnutrition is responsible for
premature deaths of over 700 children under 5 years of age
everyday in different parts of Bangladesh, Nutrition Forum
Bangladesh (NFB), a non-government organization, disclosed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite significant improvement in the field of health and
nutrition, the prevalence of malnutrition among women of child-
bearing age and children under six in Bangladesh is still high,
NFB General Secretary Dr. Anisul Awwal told a seminar.
</P>
<P>
And 60 percent of children under six are suffering from
moderate and severe grades of malnutrition, Awwal said.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar jointly organized by the NFB and the Bangladesh
Integrated Nutrition Program, speakers said about 57 percent of
women, including adolescent girls, have BMI (Bangladesh
Malnutrition Index) below 18.5, which means the majority of
adolescent girls are suffering from chronic energy deficiency.
</P>
<P>
They said over 70 percent of pregnant women and children under
5 years of age are suffering from nutritional anemia (iron
deficiency anemia), while 30 percent of the population are
suffering from iodine deficiency disorders.
</P>
<P>
The nutrition experts termed the cases of low birth weight (LBW-
weighing less than 2.5 kilograms) as stigma, which reflects one of
the most important manifestations of maternal malnutrition in the
country. They said adolescent mothers are the major contributors
of LBW babies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
