<HEADLINE> France Against Raising Banking Rates to Support Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Economy, Finance
and Industry Laurent Fabius said on Thursday that it is not proper
for the European Central Bank (ECB) to help the euro by raising
greatly its interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg, Fabius said
what is important is to show that the European economy is on the
way of improving strongly.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think personally that it is by raising greatly the
interest rates that we can solve this question," he said.
</P>
<P>
The council of governors of the ECB is due to decide Thursday
afternoon whether to raise the interest rates on a big scale or
not,
</P>
<P>
Euro has fallen below 0.92 U.S. dollar this week and its value
has decreased by 30 percent since it was launched in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Fabius said that an intervention by the ECB by raising interest
rates can only solve the problem of inflation, but France is not
experiencing any inflation for the moment.
</P>
<P>
"This type of measure can justify itself while there are the
inflationary pushes, in France we don't see them today," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
