<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Bridge Gap Between Bio-Scientists, Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) formed a
special group on Thursday to better inform the general public
about the new advances of life sciences and their benefits for
humans.
</P>
<P>
Philippe Busquin, EU commissioner in charge of research, urged
Europe to promote biotechnology and to adopt a general strategy by
taking greater account of the scientists' views on the
opportunities and risks associated with biosciences.
</P>
<P>
Eleven bio-scientists, chosen to form the high-level group on
biosciences, will examine the wide-ranging challenges and
opportunities that the development of life sciences raises for the
society.
</P>
<P>
"I want to ask scientists back to the debating table as Europe
needs to make sure that it has a sound basis for discussing these
issues," said Busquin. "A conscious political decision in this
field is not possible without informed advice and public debate,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
"Advances in life sciences research are generating significant
opportunities for improving the quality of life for European
citizens," stressed the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Complex issues associated with these advances, however, are
raising considerable uncertainty and concerns among the general
public and policy makers, Busquin said.
</P>
<P>
A recent EU-wide survey found that the European public is now
well informed about the bioscientific issues.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether they were adequately informed on
biotechnology, among the 16,082 people surveyed last November and
December within the 15-nation bloc, only 11 percent of them said
they "yes", while 81 percent felt they were not adequately
informed and the remaining 8 percent could not be sure.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that the EU citizens were more worried
about the food safety than environmental protection though both
have been undergoing changes caused by genetically modified
organisms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
