<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Government's Role Crucial to Economic Recovery, Neiss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- In Asia's economic recovery,
the most important role of a government is to create a favorable
climate for sustainable economic growth, a former International
Monetary Fund official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his exclusive interview with Xinhua here on Thursday, Hubert
Neiss, chairman of the Asia Pacific Head Office of Deutsche Bank
AG in Singapore, said that in the past few years since the crisis,
the most important role of the government was to promote the
recovery and make the recovery sustainable, and this has been done
by completing a number of reforms, because only in a climate of
economic growth can all the new technologies be absorbed.
</P>
<P>
"Over the next two years, there will be major adjustments and a
technology revolution, and governments of the Asian countries
should provide the overall favorable conditions," Neiss said.
</P>
<P>
Neiss, who used to be the chairman of the Asian Regional
Department of International Monetary Fund, said that it is the
governments' duty to maintain strong economic growth and to reform
financial systems and corporations so that financial support is
available to channel into new technologies. And governments have
to support redirection of education to produce right qualified
people to be efficient with new technologies, Neiss stressed.
</P>
<P>
What the Asian countries have learned from the recession is
that they need a sound banking system, Neiss said. "If the banking
system is weak, the whole economy is vulnerable to any shocks," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
So they have closed unreliable banks, improved the management,
set up corporations that take the bad assets from the banks so
that banks' balance sheets get clean, Neiss said. Very importantly,
he added, they have set up strong banking supervision authorities
so that banks are obliged to correspond to regulations which
reflect the best international practices.
</P>
<P>
Also, the crisis has shown that many corporations' financial
structure was very weak, Neiss said. Credits to corporations have
been rescheduled or converged into expertise, or, in some cases,
the debts of corporations are reduced so that corporations are
merged with the sound financial structure and the cleaned balance
sheets and corporations are qualified again to receive credit, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
In many countries, Neiss said, the degree of competition in
economy has been strengthened, and monopolies have been dismantled,
particularly in Indonesia. Also, the economies have become more
open, bringing in capital and expertise from abroad to strengthen
their competitiveness and efficiency, he added.
</P>
<P>
Changes have taken place in the legal system. Several countries
have made new laws to improve bankruptcy proceedings, especially
in Thailand and Indonesia. "That is very important to speed up
economic restructuring, but new laws alone are not enough, and you
need the courts which actually implement these laws in an
effective way," Neiss added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on China's economic reforms, Neiss said that China
has done very well during the crisis, the economic growth was
maintained at a high rate, and by keeping the Renminbi stable, it
has contributed to the stability in the regional markets.
</P>
<P>
Now, China started to get used to keeping economic growing,
particularly to rely more on private demand and consumption rather
than public, and tackle the same reforms that other countries are
to make in banking system and in corporations, which means the
state-owned enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
"The difference is that many countries had to make these
reforms during the recession while China can make the reforms in
an expanding economy. It is much more easier," Neiss said.
</P>
<P>
Neiss has studied China's economic policies for over 20 years
and paid close attention to the country's development. He has
visited many of China's big cities and met scores of Chinese
officials in banking and financial sectors, including Premier Zhu
Rongji when Zhu was the governor of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Neiss was attending the Business Week's CFO Forum from April 26
to 28 in Hong Kong. Over 150 Asian business leaders attended the
regional financial forum, focusing their attention on issues on
remaking Asian business, aligning information technology strategy
with business objectives, treasury and risk management, and e-
commerce in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
