<HEADLINE> China to Link Major Habitats of Giant Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China will link major habitats of
giant pandas in Sichuan, Shaanxi and Gansu provinces in western
region to facilitate breeding of the world most endangered animal.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in "Science Times", 17 "belt zones for
panda propagation" will be built to connect the Minshan, Qionglai
mountains in Sichuan, Qinling Mountain in Shaanxi and the vast
panda habitat in the southwestern region of Gansu.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 700 giant pandas, or 80 percent of
the total population in wild, are living in these regions.
</P>
<P>
Vegetation in the regions will be restored, and farmer
residents will be moved away to minimize the influence of human
activities to giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ruisheng, secretary-general of China Wildlife Conservation
Association, was quoted as saying that building the belt zones
aims at providing the pandas with a wider living space to avoid
inbreeding.
</P>
<P>
Recent research results show that genetic diversity of the
panda has decreased by 40 percent compared to two decades ago, and
the danger of extinction of small population less than 50 has
greatly increased.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
