<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 646 Chinese Officials Investigated for Malfeasance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's procuratorates have
handled more than 76,000 cases related to malfeasance of
government employees over the past three years, in which 646
officials involved have been investigated or further punished.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total 76,069 cases, 26,827 cases are undergoing the
investigative procedure, in which the suspects were accused of
abusing power, malpractice, bending the law for personal benefit,
or infringing citizens' personal and democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
Two minister-level officials were among the investigated
officials whose previous ranks were at the county level or higher,
including Xu Yunhong, former alternate member of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China and the Party secretary
of Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Xu took advantage of his position to seek personal benefit and
was the first minister-level official prosecuted in the history of
China.
</P>
<P>
China's top prosecutor Han Zhubin has urged procurators
nationwide to "seriously investigate and deal with malpractice and
power abuse among government staffs, particularly law-enforcers,
as part of the nation's anti-corruption campaign."
</P>
<P>
"Grave neglect of duty of some government employees has caused
frequent and horrible disasters such as collapsed buildings and
bridges, and fires and explosions," Han, procurator-general of the
Supreme People's Procuratorate, said at a national meeting here
today.
</P>
<P>
"Blind policy-making by some officials has caused huge losses
of state property to threaten the country's economic safety," he
told the procurators, who discussed how to fight against
malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
Major cases handled in the 1997-1999 period also included
substandard construction projects as a result of quality
negligence, confessions forced by law-enforcers, and infringement
of personal rights in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Because of the procurators' effort to handle malpractice cases
in state-owned enterprises, direct economic losses totaling 1.45
billion yuan (175 million U.S. dollars) have been prevented over
the past three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
