<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Experts Urge Less Medicine Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- As Nepal is importing more
medicines than necessary, drug experts called on the Nepali
government to limit the importation of medicines, The Kathmandu
Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is currently importing 11,000 brands of medicine, which
is one of the highest in terms of brands to the population ratio
in the world, the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
However, the avalanche of such medicines has made it difficult
for the regulatory authority to control the quality of drugs,
thereby increasing the risk for patients, the paper quoted drug
experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
The experts urged the government to revoke drugs import
licenses and reduce the import of medicine gradually.
</P>
<P>
"Import of a wide variety of drugs has messed up the monitoring
mechanism of drugs and has increased the use of ineffective
medicines," said Pradeep Pandy, chairman of the Association of
Pharmaceutical Producers of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of Nepal's imported drugs come from India,
including antibiotics and many other medicines.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to streamline the brands of imported drugs, the
Department of Drugs Administration issued a public notice recently
to ban the import of 186 drugs which failed to meet the standard
set by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
But experts believed the government should do more to change
the scenario. They argued for the development of domestic medicine
production.
</P>
<P>
"More than 80 percent of the necessary drugs can be produced in
the country if the government provides facilities to the domestic
manufacturers," said Shanker Ghimire, managing director of Asian
Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
At present, the domestic drugs manufacturers produce over 1,200
brands of medicine which meets 20 percent of the national demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
