<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Securities Regulators Deliver Penalty on Listed Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC) has delivered its penalty on the Daqing Lianyi
Petrochemical Co., Ltd. for providing misleading information
during its initial public offering (IPO) in 1996 and in its 1997
annual report.
</P>
<P>
According to the company's announcement on the Shanghai
Securities News today, the CSRC charges the company in northeast
China's Daqing City, an oil-producing town in Heilongjiang
Province, to recover 480 million yuan it raised through the IPO
and invest it in projects promised in its prospectus.
</P>
<P>
Xue Yonglin, former chairman of the board of directors, was
banned from taking senior management positions in any listed
company or securities companies for signing the 1997 annual report,
which recorded a non-existent profit of 28 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Eight members of the board of directors were warned and fined
for signing the prospectus and the 1997 annual report.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dasheng, chairman of the board of directors during the
IPO, escaped penalty for falsifying documents and fraud because of
his sudden death.
</P>
<P>
According to information disclosed by Chinese authorities in
November 1999, officials of the company were also suspected of
bribery, corruption and embezzlement of public fund. Thirty-nine
government and company officials involved in the case were
punished.
</P>
<P>
Xue Yugui, chairman of the board of supervisors, and several
other company officials were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
The authorities decided that the company and its officials
would be penalized by CSRC in accordance with the Securities Law.
</P>
</TEXT>
