<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Criticizes Britain for Conditional Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Industry and Commerce
Minister Nathan Shamuyarira Thursday criticized the British
government for laying down pre-conditions prior to the crucial
negotiations on the land acquisition program of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The minister questioned the British conditional offer a day
before Thursday's meeting expected to pave the way for the
resumption of financial assistance for the land reform program.
</P>
<P>
Shamuyarira, who is a member of the Zimbabwean delegation in
London, for the talks, described the move by Britain as
unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that they have put minimum conditions," he
said in a telephone interview with The Zimbabwe News Agency.
"You do not start negotiations by putting conditions. We will
discuss these conditions at the meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain has offered financial assistance on condition Zimbabwe
ordered the war veterans from commercial farms they had been
occupying, parliamentary elections be held soon and the rule of
law is upheld.
</P>
<P>
Britain is prepared to offer a conditional package of 36
million pounds Sterling for the Zimbabwe's land acquisition
program.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions are not difficult to fulfil," said Shamuyarira.
 "We, as a government, want to see the end of violence. We have
been fighting for the rule of law. Police are arresting people.
The issue on elections is a none issue."
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe would not order war veterans to pull out from
about 1, 000 commercial farms they had been occupying in the last
two months.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean delegation, he said, was still optimistic about
the outcome of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
London insists it was committed to supporting a transparent,
fair and cost effective program of land reform.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has told London it would compulsorily acquire farms
for resettlement if Britain failed to provide funds for
compensating farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
