<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Champ Nearly Quits over Doping Suspicion (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Olympic and world singles and
doubles champion Liu Guoliang had thought of quitting the sport
and running away from spotlight after being notified last October
of a positive test of his.
</P>
<P>
"You can hardly imagine what kind of life I led in the past six
months," said the 24-year-old Chinese, who was on Wednesday
cleared by the International Table Tennis Federation of any doping
offense.
</P>
<P>
"I told my brother that I would retire although I am able to
win at least one gold medal from the Olympic Games this summer and
the 2001 world championships," said Liu. His brother Guodong is a
coach on the Chinese Army Team.
</P>
<P>
Liu had tested positive for elevated levels of epitestosterone
August 8, when he won the world singles championship in the
Netherlands. He had tested negative a day earlier after taking the
men's doubles with Kong Linghui.
</P>
<P>
ITTF notification of his positive test came on October 24, 1999,
when he was playing the Austrian Open.
</P>
<P>
The world table tennis ruling body cleared Liu after a three-
month investigation, including two unannounced tests in February.
The Chinese Table Tennis Association told Xinhua on Wednesday the
ITTF investigation showed "no evidence for exogenous origin of
epitestosterone" and "no doping offense".
</P>
<P>
"It was a shock when I heard of positive test," Liu recalled,
voice shaking. "How could this happen to me. Someone said I had
been lucky, but I won 10 Olympic, world championships and World
Cup titles with my own efforts, and I won cleanly and fairly.
</P>
<P>
"Should I have been punished for winning too many, don't punish
me in this way. Just let me lose forever. Or just take away 10
gold medals and give me a clean name."
</P>
<P>
Liu didn't know why a positive test followed a negative one. "I
was negative on August 7. I didn't eat breakfast next morning. I
just drank a cup of milk before the games. I have been very
careful with eating and drinking. I never drink a bottle of water
which is not opened by myself," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to look back the past six months. When I was driving
alone, tears rolled down my cheeks. I couldn't help it," Liu
admitted.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the Chinese officials and coaches had never lost trust
in him.
</P>
<P>
"Minutes after we lost to Sweden in the final (of the world
team championship in Kuala Lumpur in February), when Li Furong
whispered into my ears: 'Guoliang, I understand you, trust you, I
nearly burst into tears," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Li, a former world table tennis champion, is vice president of
both the Chinese Olympic Committee and the Chinese Table Tennis
Association.
</P>
<P>
"The nightmare is over. I feel relieved now," said Liu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
