<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Make Draw over World Cup Fate of African Contenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- FIFA, soccer's world
governing body, will on Friday supervise a draw in Zurich deciding
the 25 African World Cup survivors into five groups.
</P>
<P>
African Football Confederation (CAF) spokesman Viken
Djizmedjian said the countries would be seeded based on 1998 World
Cup and 1998 and 2000 African Nations Cup results.
</P>
<P>
Djizmedjian said geography would not be considered because FIFA
wanted the best five African teams at the 2002 finals in Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon, Morocco, Nigeria, South Africa and Tunisia
represented Africa at the 1998 finals in France and all safely
cleared their first obstacles last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Other qualifers are Algeria, Angola, Burkina Faso, Congo, DR
Congo, Egypt, Ghana, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Liberia, Libya,
Madagascar, Malawi, Namibia, Senegal, Sierra Leone, Sudan, Togo,
Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The mini-league programme begins over the weekend of June 16-18
and ends on July 29 2001 with the five group winners advancing to
the first World Cup staged in Asia and the first to be co-hosted.
</P>
</TEXT>
