<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Mulls Release of Palestinian Murderers: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is examining the possibility of releasing Palestinian
inmates "with Israelis' blood on their hands," who were jailed in
Israeli prisons for murdering Jews.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of such releases, including seven Palestinian
killers who have served their terms for more than 20 years, will be
discussed at some stage in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, the
local Ha'aretz daily Thursday quoted a senior political source as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The new position might mark a policy change on the issue as
Israel's traditional release criteria prohibited freeing those
prisoners convicted of murdering Israelis, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, Israel's General Security Service (Shin
Bet) submitted a recommendation to Barak about the release of
Palestinian prisoners within the framework of the 1993 Oslo peace
accords between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Shin Bet recommended that any future release of the
prisoners should not be carried out on the basis of their criminal
actions, but only on the basis of their affiliated organization.
</P>
<P>
All prisoners, who belong to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's
Fatah movement and other Palestinian organizations supporting the
Oslo peace process, should thus be released immediately,
irrespective of what they were convicted of.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all prisoners belonging to the Islamic militant group
Hamas and Islamic Jihad, who are adamantly opposed to the peace
process, should remain in jail until their terms are finished.
</P>
<P>
The new release criterion of Shin Bet was reportedly based on
experience of previous releases, showing that the released Fatah
prisoners would join the Palestinian National Authority bureaucracy
and become an adamant force supporting the peace talks, while the
Hamas prisoners tended to return to their militant operations.
</P>
<P>
The Shin Bet opinion reportedly garnered support from some
cabinet ministers, including Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-
Ami, and officers of other security bodies and the Israel Defense
Forces.
</P>
<P>
However, the right-wing Likud party had warned that such a
recommendation should be rejected by the government as the new
release approach is "politically foolish and a moral crime."
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure, Barak initially decided to turn down the
recommendation. But the Ha'aretz report said Thursday that Barak
will reconsider his position on the issue if the final-status talks
between Israel and the Palestinians are concluded successfully.
</P>
<P>
A two-week session of such peace talks between negotiators from
both sides is scheduled to begin in Israel's Red Sea resort city of
Eilat on April 30, after two rounds in the United States earlier
failed to bring about any major breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Palestinian chief negotiator for interim issues Saeb
Erekat and his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran already met in Jericho
to discuss further release of Palestinian prisoners, but no
substantial progress was made.
</P>
<P>
Erekat reportedly had submitted a list of prisoners it wants
released. The Palestinian side insist that the two sides must agree
on who are to be freed, while Israelis said the list can only be
decided by them.  Israel has freed nearly 400 Palestinians and
other Arab prisoners in the past few years under a series of
interim peace deals, including the Sharm el Sheikh Memorandum,
which Barak and Arafat signed last December.
</P>
<P>
The latest release of 15 prisoners happened on March 20, at the
end of the four-day Muslim festival Eid al-Adha, or Feast of
Sacrifice. 
</P>
<P>
According to Palestinian senior political sources, Israel is
still holding 1,550 Palestinian prisoners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
