<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Judiciary Defends Closure of Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary on
Thursday defended its recent closure of a number of reformist
papers and periodicals, criticizing "certain groups and people" for
objecting the move.
</P>
<P>
These periodicals and dailies were closed down because they had
published articles against religious sanctities and social rights
as well as pillars of the holy Islamic system, said a statement
issued by the Justice Department in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, the judiciary suspended the publication of
10 dailies and 4 periodicals in an unprecedented move to crack down
on the country's reformist press.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the stepped-up efforts of the conservatives,
who are the real rulers of the Islamic country, to curb the
reformist campaign which has been growing since President Mohammed
Khatami took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Reformers allied to Khatami won a landslide victory in the
February parliamentary election, ending the long time conservative
majority in the legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The victory, however, has prompted a backlash from the
conservatives, who have recently used their power to jail reformist
journalists and close down reformist papers.
</P>
<P>
The statement criticized "certain groups and people", especially
the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance, for expressing
unsound and unexpected views on the "legal and religious" move to
order the temporary closure of the papers, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It referred to certain articles of the Press Law, saying that
dailies shall be free to publish unless they violate the
foundations and rules of Islam and public rights.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance Tuesday frowned
at the closure of reformist papers, saying the act will damage the
press freedom atmosphere in the country.
</P>
<P>
To muzzle the press will be to prevent healthy public
information system nationally and generate and reinforce
politically destructive rumors, said an official communique issued
by the ministry, which has constitutional supervision over the
publications in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, led by press freedom advocate Ataollah Mohajerani,
called on government branches to recognize the dignity of the craft
of journalism and eschew from any measure that might restrict the
constitutional freedom of the press in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Other groups, such as the Association of Journalists and the
Islamic Commission of Human Rights, also condemned the judiciary's
move. Students from major Iranian cities also launched protests
against the move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
