<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Presidential Election Starts Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Eleven candidates will be competing
for the next Turkish presidency as the first round of voting takes
place in the parliament after 15:00 local time (1200 GMT) on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the presiding judge of the Constitutional Court
Ahmet Sezer, who is the joint candidate of the three ruling parties
and the two main oppositions Virtue Party and True Path Party, and
parliament speaker Yildirim Akbulut are seen as the strongest
contenders.
</P>
<P>
While Sezer, who is from outside the parliament, has secured the
support of the leaders of all five parties represented in the
legislative body, Akbulut is relying on the support he expects to
get from those deputies who resent the party leaders' nomination of
a non-deputy candidate.
</P>
<P>
Akbulut poses serious challenge to Sezer as he reacted angrily
to the consensus reached by the five party leaders, saying that "
you will do an injustice to parliament if you say that no president
can come out of this parliament. As the speaker, I protest such an
attitude."
</P>
<P>
As a former prime minister and interior minister as well as a
three-time Speaker, "I am an impartial and sufficiently experienced
candidate for the presidency," Akbulut told the deputies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Sezer will likely win out in the first round
if deputies submit to their party leaders' will.
</P>
<P>
In the secret ballots, however, some maverick deputies may
repeat their defections seen during last month's vote, which dashed
the coalition leaders' hope to pass a constitutional amendment for
President Suleyman Demirel's second term in office.
</P>
<P>
Party leaders are attempting to have Sezer elected by the end of
the first three rounds without having to stage a fourth and final
round.
</P>
<P>
According to the election procedures, a candidate needs a two-
thirds (367 votes) majority in the 550-seat Grand National Assembly
(parliament) to win the electionsin the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
If deputies fail to choose a president in the first two rounds,
276 votes will be sufficient in the third and fourth rounds.
</P>
<P>
The third round will take place on May 5, and in case of
failure, two candidates who win the highest votes in the third
round will attend the last round.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election in the parliament must be concluded
before Demirel steps down on May 16.
</P>
<P>
If agreement can't be reached in the fourth round, parliament
will be dissolved immediatly for a new general election in
accordance with the Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
