<HEADLINE> Indonesian Parliament Supports Wahid's Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We still gives support to the president (Wahid). But we urge
him to pay more attention on the on-going economic recovery
program. So far, we still don't think about withdrawing our
political backing. But we will remind him and may criticize him,"
House Speaker Akbar Tandjung told reporters after attending a
Consultation Meeting with the president at the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
But, Tandjung said that there is no guarantee from the House
that in the future there will be no problem in connection with
such support to keep its political backing to the president to run
this country for five years.
</P>
<P>
"No, I can't give such a guarantee that there will be no
problem in the future,"Tandjung said without details.
</P>
<P>
"I can say that so far, there is no problem at all with our
support. But we see that there is many critical views, and will be
many critical views which are directed to him in connection with
his policies," Tandjung added.
</P>
<P>
Tandjung further said that in the course of the meeting, both
sides(president and the House) discussed many recent issues such
as replacement of cabinet ministers, the on-going economic
recovery program, and the possible removal of the MPR decree on
communism.
</P>
<P>
"But the most important point is that we urge the president to
pay more attention on economic issues. Because, as we know, so far
there is no significant signs that foreign investors are
interested to come and invest their capital here due to
uncertainty of the political situation in this country. We are
really concerned and have urged the president to be serious on
this point," Tandjung said.
</P>
<P>
Wahid infuriated his main coalition partners on Tuesday when he
sacked two ministers, and some party leaders had threatened to
withdraw their members from the cabinet in protest.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal of the ministers from the two biggest political
parties in the parliament caused deep concern in local financial
markets, sending them to six-month lows on fears that a growing
divide between Wahid and some of his coalition partners would
further delay the country's ongoing economic recovery program.
</P>
</TEXT>
