<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Prize Money Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The total prize money for this
year's Wimbledon tennis championships will be increased by 6.1 per
cent.
</P>
<P>
With the increase, the total prize money will stand at 8.06
million pounds (12.69 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The organizers brushed aside pressure from top women players to
give them equal prize money with the men but announced total prize
money for the women would rise 7.9 percent compared with 4.8
percent for the men.
</P>
<P>
In a statement the organizers said it was "a move aimed at
recognizing and further promoting an increase in the depth of the
women's game."
</P>
<P>
The men's singles champion will receive 477,500 pounds (752,000
U.S. dollars) compared with 455,000 (716,500 U.S. dollars) last
year, while the women's champion will win 430,000 pounds (677,200
U.S. dollars) compared with 409,500 (644,900 U.S. dollars) in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
