<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Set to Transfer to Palestinians Village Near Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak intends to transfer soon to full Palestinian control the
village of Abu Dis, as an "advance" of Israel's next troop
redeployment in the West Bank, the local daily Ha'aretz Thursday
quoted a senior political source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to bring the proposal to his Security Cabinet
for approval next week and such a move will allay Palestinian
suspicions that Israel intends to use delaying tactics in the talks
so as to avoid transferring significant territory to the
Palestinians, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dis, which is adjacent to Jerusalem, is now part of the so-
called Area B, where Israel is in control of security while the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) exercises civilian
administration.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat requested Barak a few months ago to
transfer Abu Dis to full Palestinian control as stipulated in the
Sharm el Sheikh peace deal signed last September.
</P>
<P>
When Barak brushed aside the request on the account that the
transfer of areas close to Jerusalem entailed political problems
and that it would be better to wait for the permanent settlement,
Arafat suspended the talks with Israel for two months.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between Israel and the Palestinians, Israel
will transfer to the Palestinians the areas of the West Bank that
are not "specified military locations" or areas the status of which
will be decided in the permanent settlement, such as Jerusalem and
the Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Based on this, the PNA's position is that Israel must vacate at
least 90 percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Vacillates on U.N. Presence in South Amid Syrian "Doubts" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
drew back what he said on Wednesday about the presence of
international peace-keeping force in south Lebanon after scheduled
Israeli pullout, Oriental Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said Lebanon will not "guard the border for Israel" and the
presence of the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) in
south Lebanon should get the Lebanese government's permission
</P>
<P>
Hoss held Israel responsible for any blunder that may happen in
south Lebanon after its withdrawal as the Jewish state did not
realize a comprehensive peace with Arabic countries, the radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Hoss said on Wednesday that Lebanon will invite UNIFIL
to fill the vacuum in south Lebanon after Israel's pullout by July
and assured that the situation will be under control so as to
enable the legitimate authorities to extend their sovereignty of
the sea, air and land to the liberated areas.
</P>
<P>
However, Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh, whose country is
Lebanon's main power broker, cast doubt on Wednesday on the ability
of the U.N. to maintain security in south Lebanon, saying a
deployment of international forces after the impending Israeli
withdrawal was "highly sensitive and hypothetical."
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL is expected to be reinforced from the current 4,500
members to 7,000 if it should take on the peacekeeping task in
south Lebanon after Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese leaders have never declared that the Lebanese army will
be deployed in the vacated area in south Lebanon. Lebanon has
reiterated that it will not guarantee the security of northern
Israel as Palestinian guerrillas will fight for the right to go
home.
</P>
<P>
Some 360,000 Palestinian refugees have been taking shelter in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has notified the U.N. that it is determined to pull out
its troops from south Lebanon completely by July with or without an
agreement with Lebanon or Syria, which has 35,000 troops deployed
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied parts of south Lebanon since 1978. It set up
the present "security zone" in 1985 with the excuse of protecting
its northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
