<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Target Date for Framework Deal May be Postponed: Israeli Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The target date for concluding a
framework agreement on the final-status issues between Israel and
the Palestinians will likely be put off again from the end of May
to the end of June, the Israeli daily Ha'aretz reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted political sources as saying that two months
of work will be needed to complete the agreement and prepare for a
trilateral summit in Washington at which U.S. President Bill
Clinton will host Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
A similar signal was sent by United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who said in Washington on Wednesday that in the
six or eight weeks ahead, "very intensive" work will be needed on
the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Clinton told Arafat in Washington last
week that a summit will be held only if substantial progress is
made in the talks with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The previous round of Israeli-Palestinian talks, held at a U.S.
Air Force base near Washington, ended two weeks ago with the
preparation of a two-page "skeleton agreement," which specifies the
clauses to be included in the framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are supposed to ameliorate the skeleton agreement and
start fleshing it out in the next round of talks to be held on
April 30 in the Israeli Red Sea city of Eilat, about 200 kilometers
south of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Mideast special envoy Dennis Ross is expected to
monitor the Eilat talks and conduct a shuttle between Barak and
Arafat in a bid to speed up the adoption of decisions.
</P>
<P>
Ross will give Barak a detailed report on the Arafat-Clinton
talks when he arrives in Israel at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sharm el Sheikh agreement signed last year,
Israel and the Palestinians were to have reached a framework
agreement on the final-status issues on February 13.
</P>
<P>
After missing the deadline without anything on paper regarding
the final-status issues such as the fate of Jerusalem, the Jewish
settlement and Palestinian refugees, both sides compromised over a
three-month postponement of the framework deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Negotiates for Release of Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao,said in a radio interview that he has sent a
representative to negotiate with the rebels who are demanding a 2.
4-million-U.S.-dollar ransom for the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, also heading the Moro National Liberation Front, was
appointed Wednesday by Philippine President Joseph Estrada as the
government's negotiator with the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado confirmed
Wednesday that the hostages abducted from Malaysia had been found
in Sulu province, about an hour's boat ride from Sipadan Island,
Malaysia where the abduction took place.
</P>
<P>
Mercado, who visited Sulu on Wednesday, also confirmed the
participation of the Muslim rebel group Abu Sayyaf in the
abduction.
</P>
<P>
He said the hostages have been divided into several groups and
are being moved around the town of Talipao, 16 km away from Jolo,
the capital city of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said the hostages are "safe, sound and alive" in the
hands of the captors, adding that "our prime concern will always
be the safety of the captives."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mercado said he has given military officials the
blanket authority on what actions to take against the captors.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller of two groups fighting for an
independent Islamic state in Mindanao. They are under attack at
their stronghold in Basilan province by Philippine troops trying
to rescue some 27 hostages kidnapped on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The other rebel Muslim group is the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front which has been fighting for an independent Muslim state
during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
The hostages seized in Malaysia on Sunday include two Filipinos,
at least eight Malaysians, three Germans, two French nationals,
two South Africans, Two Finns and a Lebanese woman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
