<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Australian Aborigines Live Without Reliable  Water, Sewerage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Many Australian Aboriginal
communities are living without reliable power and water supplies
or working sewerage systems, the Australian Bureau of Statistics
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's survey found that while almost all permanent
dwellings in Aboriginal communities were connected to water, power
and sewerage, there were substantial problems with the operation
of the services.
</P>
<P>
It found that in the 348 communities with a population of 50 or
more people, 58 communities' water supply failed testing.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found 57 communities had frequent power
interruptions and 204 had leakage or overflows in the sewerage
systems.
</P>
<P>
The survey, commissioned by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander Commission, found that almost 110,000 people, or 27
percent of Australia's estimated indigenous population, live in 1,
300 locations identified as discrete indigenous communities.
</P>
<P>
About one in three permanent homes in the communities required
major repair or replacement, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
