<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Presidency Denies Plot to Oust Senate President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Presidency Wednesday
refuted allegations of sponsoring a plot to oust Senate President
Chuba Okadigbo, stressing that events in the National Assembly
were purely internal.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper quoted Information
Minister Jerry Gana as saying at the end of Wednesday's Federal
Executive Council (FEC) meeting that he wondered why the
Presidency could embark on such a scheme in view of its pledge to
uphold the integrity of the nation and the public good.
</P>
<P>
Most Nigerian newspapers Wednesday reported alleged attempt of
the presidency to organize impeachment of Okadigbo and his deputy
Haruna Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The National Assembly may have created problems
within itself. The reaction to the impeachment moves against
President Olusegun Obasanjo has been that of wide condemnation
all over the country and in some parts of the world and if there
are certain reactions to that, they have nothing to do with the
Presidency."
</P>
<P>
Gana said the problems of the National Assembly were purely
internal, he pointed out that if anything was happening with the
leadership of the Upper House, it might be a fallout of the
impeachment plot against President Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that "the crisis is not from the
Presidency of the Federal Republic of Nigeria, because both the
Judiciary, National Assembly and the Executive are one
government.
</P>
<P>
"The three are very important to the survival of democracy. The
 Presidency having the overall leadership cannot afford to
destabilize any arm of government because that will cause
instability in the whole administration."
</P>
<P>
The information minister said, "people underrated Nigerian's
reactions and resolve to protect their democracy and against
dictatorship. We should even be pitied and now what they started
is backfiring on them.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you, Nigerians would be angry with anybody who
wants to destabilize their most cherished democracy. Please don't
blame the executive for the crisis in the National Assembly," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
