<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Price Fluctuation Blamed for Ghana's Currency Devaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's Finance Minister Kwame
Peprah said the steep decline in the price of cocoa and rise in
the price of oil in the world market led to the devaluation of the
country's currency cedi, Ghana News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cedi devaluated more than eighty percent last year, according
to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Peprah said in the west African country's capital Accra on
Wednesday that in 1998 Ghana sold a ton of cocoa for 1,600 U.S.
dollars and bought crude oil at 11 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we are selling a ton of cocoa at 800 dollars and buying
a barrel of crude oil at about 22 dollars."
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said "there is light at the tunnel" as
government has initiated moves with its donor partners to fill in
the projected gap of 150 million dollars in cash flow as export
earnings have steeply declined.
</P>
<P>
Peprah said the government has advanced the inflow of 200
million dollars due in the second half of the year to the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
He announced that 50 million dollars has already been received
and the remaining 150 million dollars is expected shortly.
</P>
<P>
Peprah said the Ghanaian economy has been and is still too
import dependent in spite of efforts made to curb it.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that the nation's ability to continue to maintain
current import levels depends on its ability not just to export
more, but to change its export patterns by reducing its dependence
on cocoa with items better withstand price fluctuations in the
world market.
</P>
<P>
He said the country must reduces imports with substitution of
locally made product.  
</P>
</TEXT>
