<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Lebanon Wednesday gave its strongest hint that it will
cooperate in international efforts to maintain peace and stability
in the south of the country after the Israel Defense Forces'
scheduled withdrawal to the international border.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss said in a statement that his
country is likely to agree to the deployment of United Nations
peacekeepers in areas vacated by the IDF.
</P>
<P>
"We have to remind ourselves that the Israeli withdrawal will
not lead to a vacuum threatening security and stability as some
pessimists like to portray," Hoss told news agencies."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak intends to transfer soon to
full Palestinian control the village of Abu Dis, which is adjacent
to Jerusalem, as an "advance" on account of the IDF's third
redeployment in the West Bank, a senior political source said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to bring the proposal for approval by the
security cabinet next week. Political sources said Barak will also
ask the security cabinet and then the entire cabinet to approve "
dramatic decisions" which will reflect "Israeli positions that are
more far-reaching than in the past" with respect to the Palestinian
independence.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Barak has become much more flexible with regard
to the major issues of the permanent settlement, particularly the
amount of territory that will be transferred to the Palestinian
National Authority.
</P>
<P>
The first such decision will involve the transfer of Abu Dis,
which is now part of Area B under Israeli security and Palestinian
civilian control.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is expected to confer with
the ultra-orthodox religious Shas party's spiritual leader Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef soon, possibly on Friday, to end a long spell during
which the two have not met.
</P>
<P>
Confirming that preparations for the meeting have taken place,
high-ranking One Israel ruling coalition members said that
finalizing the Barak-Yosef encounter hinges on development in the
crisis between Shas and the left-wing Meretz party.
</P>
<P>
The impasse between the two parties has worsened in recent days,
owing to a Shas demand that a 10-million-shekel (about 2.5 million
U.S. dollars) advance be allocated to the party-affiliated
religious school system.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's health system will be hit by a general strike on
Thursday, with all state hospitals operating on Shabbat schedule.
The resumption of the strike is part of the physicians' six-week
struggle for increased wages.
</P>
<P>
The physicians' union, the Israel Medical Association (IMA),
decided to order the strike after their talks with representatives
of the Finance Ministry's wages department and budgetary branch at
the beginning of the week yielded no solution.
</P>
<P>
No further negotiations are planned for Thursday, although the
heads of the IMA struggle will convene, at which point the doctors
are expected to voice their intention of continuing the work
stoppages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
