<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Closes Down Another Reformist Weekly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary has
ordered another reformist weekly to suspend publication, raising
the number of the banned dailies and periodicals to 14.
</P>
<P>
The Ava, a socio-cultural weekly based in Najafabad of the
central Isfahan Province, was told to close down temporarily in a
press court session on Wednesday, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The session was held to investigate charges involving Mostafa
Izadi, managing director of the weekly.
</P>
<P>
Izadi was charged of libel and publication of false news,
distortion of speeches of different people and desecration of the
late supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the founder of the
Islamic Republic of Iran, an informed source said.
</P>
<P>
The conservative judiciary closed down nine reformist dailies
and three journals on Sunday and Monday following a warning of the
supreme leader Seyyed Ali Khamenei that a section of the domestic
press was propagating against Islamic principles and becoming bases
of the enemies.
</P>
<P>
The move was considered a stepped-up effort by the
conservatives, who are the real rulers of the country, to crack
down on the reformist campaign fostered by President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's allies won an overwhelming victory in February's
parliamentary election, bringing to an end the long time
conservative majority in the legislative body.
</P>
<P>
But the conservatives, despite their defeat in the election,
still control most of the powerful state organs, including the
military and the judiciary, which they can use to exert pressure on
the reformists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
