<HEADLINE> Australia's Tourist Town Isolated Because of Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The tourist town of Daintree, in
the far north of the Queensland state in northeast Australia, was
isolated by floodwaters Thursday as rain continued to cause havoc
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Police said roads to the town were cut, but there were ample
food supplies.
</P>
<P>
The continuing wet has stranded residents and motorists
throughout the waterlogged north, which has been hit by three
cyclones this year, causing hundreds of millions of Australian
dollars worth of damage to property and crops.
</P>
<P>
Emergency services were expected to make food drops to isolated
properties north of Daintree as it was not yet known when roads
would reopen, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 12 students and research assistants from the
University of Sydney, stranded in outback Queensland were expected
to be airlifted to safety later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said a helicopter that had been due to pick
them up Thursday morning had been diverted to make food drops to
properties in the north.
</P>
<P>
The group, which is studying flora and fauna in the region,
have been isolated by flood waters at their camp site since last
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
