<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Freezes Cult Leaders' Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Police have frozen two
bank accounts belonging to leaders of the Kanungu doomsday cult,
the New Vision daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One account belonged to the Dominic Kataribaabo at the
Centenary Rural Development Bank, and the other is registered
under Ishayuriro rya Maria Primary School, said the report.
The cult, the Movement for Restoration of the Ten Commandments of
God, burnt to death at least 500 of followers on March 17. Since
then the Police have discovered mass graves on the properties of
the cult leaders, bringing the number of the dead to more than
1,000.
</P>
<P>
"The Police came with a court order and we gave them the
details of the bank accounts," said Mbarara Centenary bank branch
chief Athanasius Mwesigye.
</P>
<P>
Ishayuriro rya Maria bank account had several signatories and
they withdrew most of the money days before the fire in Kanungu
on March 17, a bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The primary school, which was started by the cult, was the
headquarters of the cult. It was closed down after complaints
that the children were abused.
</P>
<P>
The Police launched an investigation last month into the
finances of the cult leaders after discovering that they had
collected millions of Uganda shillings from their followers, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Followers of the cult were required to sell all their property
and give the money to the cult before being admitted as members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Warns Religious Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said that religious extremism will not be tolerated in Uganda,
and he will ensure that Uganda remains a peaceful and organized
society.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to allow anyone to use religion to disturb
the peace we have brought about," the New Vision, a leading
newspaper in the country, quoted Museveni as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The forces of law and order are still investigating the matter
to establish whether it was a case of mass suicide or mass murder
or a combination of both, the president said in a speech read
Wednesday by Second Deputy Prime Minister Moses Ali at the
seventh graduation ceremony of the Islamic University in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
 The Movement for Restoration of the Ten Commandments of God,
a cult in the east African country, burnt at least 500 of their
followers in Kanungu in southwestern Uganda on March 17. Since
then mass graves were discovered on the properties of the cult
leaders, bringing the number of the dead to more than 1,000.
</P>
