<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Sector Still Largest Income Payer in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- State-owned businesses,
government units and organizations in Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong province, still provide the largest source of
income for local residents.
</P>
<P>
Some 66.8 percent of the disposable income for local residents
comes from the state-owned sector, reaching 8,032 yuan (967 US
dollars) per capita last year, according to the latest statistics
from the Municipal Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
This figure is due to the increased income of government
employees as well as retired civil servants last year. The annual
salary of a teacher in Guangzhou averaged 18,000 yuan (2,168 US
dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, improved performance of state-owned enterprises
resulting from restructuring also yielded more profits to pay
salaries. There are 944 state-owned enterprises in Guangzhou,
generating 5.3 billion yuan (638 million US dollars) in profits
last year, up 54.9 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth continued through the first three months of
this year. Statistics showed that the industrial added value in
Guangzhou amounted to 17.7 billion yuan (2.1 billion US dollars)
in the first three months, up 16.7 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned sector earned 22.9 billion yuan (2.7 billion US
dollars) of output value, representing an increase of 20.9 percent
compared with the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Consumer Confidence Surges to New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese consumers have expressed
their highest-level confidence in 20 months in the bright
prospects of the national economy this year, an official report
said today.
</P>
<P>
According to figures in a National Bureau of Statistics (NBS)
report released here today, steady economic growth and development
in the western part of the country helped boost the Consumer
Expectation Index to 95.7 points in March, the highest level since
August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some 63 percent of consumers believe that the economy will be
better than last year, and 39 percent of consumers expect higher
incomes in the next 12 months, according to the report. The
figures represent an increase of three and two percentage points,
respectively, higher than in February.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the consumers think that the consumer market was
better than their expectations in March.
</P>
<P>
The report also attributed the increase in consumer confidence
to the rapid growth of Internet and the high-tech industry, the
recovery of the global economy and the rebound of China's stock
market in the first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the consumers believe that the government's
move to develop the vast western areas of the country will greatly
push forward economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
According to NBS, the Index of Current Economic Conditions also
continued to rise in March, reaching 92.8 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
