<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Gov't Gives Cool Response to ANZAC Currency Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Zealand Minister of Finance Michael Cullen said here
Thursday that a joint currency with Australia "is not on the
government's agenda", though the issue is worth debating.
</P>
<P>
Cullen was responding to a study released Wednesday evening by
the Wellington-based Institute of Policy Studies, which suggests
New Zealand would benefit economically from a common currency with
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The 130-page report, commissioned by the lobby group, the
Australia-New Zealand business Council, said that an ANZAC dollar
(the proposed name for a common currency of Australia and New
Zealand)would be the logical next step in getting the two
countries' economic relations closer.
</P>
<P>
Chris Mackay, executive director of the Council, said the
growing pressures of global commerce make an Australasian currency
inevitable and it could be the first step to joining a wider
currency bloc, probably led by the United States.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement, Minister Cullen said he welcomes the debate,
but doesn't think the move is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
He said Australia's economy is about seven times bigger than
New Zealand's and a joint currency would lead to Australia
dictating New Zealand's monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of New Zealand's independence, and capacity to
control its own economic destiny, tend to weigh the balance
against monetary union," the New Zealand minister stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Kills Two New Zealand Mountaineers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The bodies of two New Zealand
students, believed to be climbers missing after an avalanche in
the Southern Alps in the east part of New Zealand's South Island,
have been found.
</P>
<P>
Television New Zealand reported in its Thursday evening program
that 17-year-old Sean Reese and 20-year-old John Haworth were
buried in snow after the avalanche on Mount Strachan, southwest of
Twizel,Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local police and search and rescue staff found the bodies
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
They are now being brought down from the mountain.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-year-old Ben Gaston escaped the slide unhurt and managed
to dig out 20-year-old Paul Hannah who sprained both knees.
</P>
<P>
Gaston then walked for six hours to use a cellphone to alert
police about his missing companions Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The two survivors are being reunited with their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
