<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E.African Police Chiefs Meet on Escalating Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- High ranking police officers from
the east African sub-region are attending a three-day meeting in
Kenya's capital Nairobi to map out the strategies against
escalating crimes.
</P>
<P>
The police chiefs from Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, the Sudan,
Ethiopia, Rwanda, Burundi as well as representatives from Interpol
Wednesday began their discussions on such issues as cross-border
crimes, illegal drugs and firearms traffic, theft of motor
vehicles and terrorism, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's police chief, Philemon Abong'o, urged the delegates to
deliberate appropriate and workable solution to tackle
cross-border crimes by developing mechanisms to increase vigilance
and genuine cooperation at all major border points.
</P>
<P>
Crimes in the region had become more complicated due to easy
movement of people, goods and services and access to fast and
modern communication facilities, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said modalities and methods must be devised to curb the high
rate of vehicle theft and eradicate illicit cultivation and
traffic in drugs in the region.
</P>
<P>
Peter Kimundi, head of Interpol's Eastern African sub-regional
bureau, emphasized that the joint security was important because
forces could not achieve much by operating solo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
