<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Speaker Slams IMF Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Speaker of the National
Assembly Amusaa Mwanamwambwa has criticized the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) policies for being stiff and hindering the
economic and social development of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the IMF parliamentarian workshop in Lusaka on
Wednesday, Mwanamwambwa said Zambia's obligation to meet IMF
benchmarks and conditions had eroded the country's ability to
adequately provide the basic social needs of the people, Times of
Zambia newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Our country's social and economic development plans are
tailored to meet the benchmarks and conditions set by the IMF and
its co-operating partners in order for Zambia to qualify for
financial assistance in form of loans and grants," the speaker was
quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said while acknowledging the efforts of the IMF and other
creditors in reducing Zambia's debt burden, it had become apparent
that debts were simply unsustainable. The total debt cancellation
would enable Zambia to jump start its economy and face the
challenges of poverty elimination more effectively.
</P>
<P>
Mwanamwambwa said Zambia had been paying debt service of about
200 million U.S. dollars a year which was twice the expenditure on
education and health over the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
