<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nike, Adidas Sue U.S. Wal-Mart Over Counterfeit Sportswear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Nike Inc., the world's
largest sportswear maker, and Adidas America, Inc., the U.S. unit
of the German sportswear giant, Wednesday jointly filed suit
against Wal-Mart Stores, alleging the retailer sells counterfeit
Nike and Adidas T-shirts at its wholesale club stores.
</P>
<P>
Adidas and Nike become the fifth and sixth major sportswear
companies to sue Wal-Mart for selling counterfeits in the last two
years, the two companies said in a statement. Nike also alleged
that Wal-Mart has been selling other counterfeit Nike products at
Sam's Club.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Tommy Hilfiger brought two actions against Wal-Mart
for selling counterfeit goods in Sam's Club, in Wal-Mart stores,
and on Wal-Mart Online. Wal-Mart paid out an unprecedented 6.4
million U.S. dollars to settle those lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
In November 1998, Polo Ralph Lauren, Nautica and Fubu lodged
similar claims for counterfeit sales against Wal-Mart. Wal-Mart
recently settled the Polo and Nautica claims by paying 565,000
dollars, while Fubu's claims are still pending.
</P>
<P>
"A suit against Wal-Mart should put the retail industry on
notice that Adidas will not tolerate sales of counterfeit goods
anywhere in the country," said Michael Heilbronner, Associate
Counsel, Intellectual Property, of Adidas America, Inc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
