<HEADLINE> Russian Troops Fight Rebel Ambush, 27 Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ten Russian servicemen, including
a senior commissioned officer, and 17 rebels were killed when
federal troops confronted another rebel ambush in Chechnya on
Wednesday, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A search group headed by Lieutenant Colonel Shevelyov
encountered a rebel band of over 50 armed men in the southern
outskirts of Serzhen-Yurt Wednesday morning. As the fighting was
raging, another group of rebels attacked the servicemen from the
rear.
</P>
<P>
A special army unit was dispatched to aid Shevelyov's men. The
rebels were scattered and 17 of them were killed, Interfax quoted
Colonel General Valery Manilov, first deputy head of the Russian
General Staff, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russian troops have come under frequent rebel ambushes lately.
Fifteen federal servicemen lost their lives in the previous rebel
attack last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The federal air force has stepped up air raids on rebel
positions in the southern mountains of the breakaway republic,
flying 70 combat missions on Wednesday alone that involved Su-25
attack planes, Su-24 bombers, An-26 and An-30 reconnaissance
aircraft and Mi-24 helicopter gunships, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The Russian media said hostilities in Chechnya might intensify
in the next few days. Interfax quoted sources as saying that the
purpose of the stepped-up campaign is to strip the rebels of their
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
