<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians' Wages Continue to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Australians' average weekly
earnings jumped 1.4 percent in the three months to February 1999,
further increasing the pressure for another rise in interest rates,
the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Economists were expecting only a modest increase in wages after
the 1.5 percent rise in November.
</P>
<P>
During the period, average male weekly earnings rose 1.6
percent seasonally adjusted to 823.80 Australian dollars (494.28 U.
S. dollars), up 13.10 Australian dollars (7.86 U.S. dollar) in
three months.
</P>
<P>
Female earnings rose just 0.9 percent to 689.40 Australian
dollars (413.64 U.S. dollars), up 6.50 Australian dollars (3.9 U.S.
dollars) for the quarter, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The figures were good news for the embattled Australian dollar,
which rose on news of the wages figures.
</P>
<P>
All eyes will now be on Friday's inflation figures, with
another bad result there likely to set the seal on a further rate
rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
