<HEADLINE> One Tourist Dead in Cambodia's Ferry Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A Cambodian tourist ferry sank
in the Tonle Sap River near Kompong Chhnang Wednesday, killing one
tourist from China's Taiwan, tourism officials confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tourist ferry, known as Royal No. 5, was on its way from
Siem Reap to Phnom Penh when it sank about 10 kilometers from
Kompong Chhnang town (about 100 kilometers north of the capital)
where the depth of the water is about four to five meters.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that there were 14 foreigners on the boat.
</P>
<P>
The true cause of the sinking is not yet available. It was said
that the boat was overloaded. The Royal's capacity was 50 people,
but witnesses and authorities said 65 passengers were packed
aboard.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodia Daily cited a ticket seller for Royal ferry, who
asked not to be named, as saying that the boat hit a tree stump in
the water shortly after 10 a.m. Wednesday and sank almost
immediately.
</P>
<P>
It was the second incident in a month in the tourist ferry
service to and from Siem Reap. On March 22, seven masked gunmen
hijacked and robbed a passenger boat on its way to Siem Reap, but
none was injured or killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
