<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Urges Sri Lanka Continue Reforms to Sustain Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has urged Sri Lanka to continue structural reforms in public
administration and the financial reform to sustain higher economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report released Wednesday, the Manila-based bank
said the government must streamline state agencies and retrench or
redeploy employees in public institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Real gross domestic product (GDP) growth (in Sri Lanka) is
projected at five percent and six percent in 2000 and 2001
respectively," the ADB said in its Asian Development Outlook 2000.
</P>
<P>
The report said the higher growth this year will be supported
by a modest rise in industrial production on the back of an
overall recovery in world trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, Sri Lanka's GDP grew by 4.2 percent in
1999, down from 4.7 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report said reforms in the public sector are necessary to
help reduce the fiscal deficit, estimated at eight percent of GDP
last year. The central bank has forecast the deficit at around 7.5
percent of GDP in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The report said the role of the domestic capital market must be
expanded to raise capital formation.
</P>
<P>
The "development finance institutions are still the major
source of long-term finance," it said.
</P>
<P>
DFCC Bank and National Development Bank, the two biggest
development banks, currently provide the majority of long-term
loans to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said a medium-term strategy for fiscal consolidation
should prioritize improved tax administration and elimination of
distortions in the system.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the ADB
have previously urged the government to reduce the number of tax
concessions granted for selected sectors as well as foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
The ADB forecast annual average inflation at 6.5 percent in
2000, compared with 4.7 percent in 1999, warning that higher world
oil prices could have an impact.
</P>
<P>
The report said poverty was widespread in the country, adding
that 21 percent of the population were "poor."
</P>
<P>
"In the short term, the government must ensure the poor gain
access to social support and continue to receive income through a
transfer scheme," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
