<HEADLINE> Thai Security Agencies in Full Alert for ADB Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai security agencies will be on
full alert to prevent the possibility of terrorist attacks during
the Asian Development Bank (ADB) conference in northern Thai city
of Chiang Mai next week, the official Thai News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The alert followed an intelligence warning that some
unspecified terrorist groups might carry out bomb threats at the
meeting, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB's annual board of governors meeting to be held in
Chiang Mai from May 6 to 8 is expected to attract about 3,200
delegates from 50 members, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said concerns over safety has prompted Thai police
authority to set aside some helicopters to assist if delegates
find themselves in difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
Police have also been ordered to set up checkpoints in and
around Chiang Mai, while immigration units have been told to keep
a close watch for suspicious people entering the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai was quoted as saying that all
agencies at the meeting will be "firm" when handling security, but
also to think about the general public.
</P>
<P>
The report also said security agencies would be keeping a close
watch on non-governmental organization and other protesters.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 police officers would be dispatched throughout
Chiang Mai during the meeting, it said. 
</P>
