<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Bank Fees Rise: Survey Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Bank fees increased
by up to 40 percent in two years as banks moved from mortgages
subsidizing savings accounts to user-pays accounts, survey
organization Cannex Australia said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Even though banks had pushed customers on to automatic teller
machines, phone banking or the Internet as low-cost alternatives
to branches, fees for these electronic services had also been
jacked up, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Cannex managing director Andrew Willink said the survey results
showing across-the-board increases between 15 and 40 per cent were
not surprising.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it surprised anyone, mainly because financial
institutions needed to shift from the benefits from the high
margins on mortgages versus the fact that on the traditional
deposit accounts they were subsidized," Willink told ABC Radio
here.
</P>
<P>
"Now it's very much a user-pays, stand-alone type of product,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said electronic transactions were cheaper than paper-based
transactions but there was still a cost incurred.
</P>
<P>
Many banks in Australia had introduced a certain number of free
electronic transactions or rebates.
</P>
<P>
"Each person is very different to how they use it and therefore
it's very hard to pinpoint whether it affects everyone in the
community," Willink said.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been a few fee decreases, mainly for deposits
and electronic pay deductions.
</P>
<P>
"But the majority of fees have increased," Willink said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Air Force to Receive 6 Hawk Jets From Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Air Force will
receive six new Hawk jet fighters from the United Kingdom in June,
according to Indonesian Military spokesman Rear Marshall Graito
Usodo.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the six British-made tactical attack aircraft will
be sent soon. This was the second batch of 40 aircraft we ordered
a couple years ago," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The six Hawks will be stationed at Supadio Air Base in
Pontianak, capital of West Kalimantan, which already has 14 Hawk-
200s.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the six Hawks were originally scheduled to
arrive in September last year but were delayed following the
crisis in East Timor. Anti-independence militias in East Timor
went on a spree of killing and destruction after East Timorese
voted overwhelmingly to throw off Indonesia rule on August 30 last
year.
</P>
<P>
Following the crisis, the European Union placed an arms embargo
on Indonesia restricting purchases to black box instruments such
as radar. The embargo was lifted in January.
</P>
<P>
Unlike previous deliveries which were directly flown to
Indonesia, the six new aircraft would be shipped in containers and
assembled upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia ordered 40 Hawk-100 aircraft and Hawk-200 aircraft
worth around 120 million U.S. dollars in May 1996. Fourteen of the
aircraft have been delivered since April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in 1993, Indonesia bought 24 Hawk aircraft, the
delivery of which was completed in May 1997. The 24 Hawks are
stationed in Pekanbaru, capital of Riau province.
</P>
<P>
The Hawk-200 is a single-seat multi-role combat plane made by
British Aerospace. It is usually fitted with a Rolls-Royce Adour
Mk 871 engine which can produce a maximum speed of 1,065
kilometers per hour. It can carry up to 3,000 kilograms in rockets
and bombs on seven under-wing external points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
