<HEADLINE> NZ Businesses Favor Sharing Currency with Australia: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Eighty percent of New Zealand's
businesses want to share a common currency with Australia,
Wellington's Institute of Policy Studies research has found.
</P>
<P>
Institute Director Arthur Grimes Thursday told the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) radio here that the study found an
overwhelming number of businesses supported a single trans-Tasman
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Grimes said a common currency would have major benefits for New
Zealand's businesses.
</P>
<P>
"It makes the cost of doing business for New Zealand firms a
lot less, and particularly for firms that are exporting or for
those ones who are importing raw materials from Australia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said there would be longer-term advantages for Australia.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has obtained advantages from the free trade
agreement between Australia and New Zealand, partly by increasing
its trade with New Zealand, but in particular in terms of its
reputation and credibility in the wider Asia-Pacific region," he
added.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Trade Minister Jim Sutton also told the ABC radio
that he was delighted this issue is now being taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
"Until very recently it was in the political category of
unthinkable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first survey of any element of public opinion I've
heard of that has shown significant support for monetary union,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Sutton said the concept would have to be tested over coming
years in the community.
</P>
<P>
"But I think at the very least this is a straw in the wind," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Builds Over 1,850 Km of Roads in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar built a total of 1,858.5
kilometers (km) of roads in towns and rural areas in fiscal 1999-
2000 which ended in March, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Colonel Thein Nyunt, Myanmar's minister of Progress of
Border Areas and National Races and Development Affairs, the
report said the roads built during the fiscal year include tarred,
stone, gravel and earth roads.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year, water supply projects were implemented in
10 towns in Kachin, Rakhine and northern Shan states and Sagaing
and Yangon divisions, bringing the total number of towns in which
such projects have been implemented up to this year to 160, the
minister said at a work coordination meeting of the ministry here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar designated the 1999-2000 fiscal year as the road and
bridge year and the water supply year.
</P>
<P>
The authorities admitted that towns in the country have made
progress to some extent but in rural areas, the rate of
development is slow.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar has built 5,871 km of
roads since 1988 and the total length of roads in the country had
been extended to 29,187 km in 1999 from 23,316 km in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
