<HEADLINE> Mexico Asks U.S. to Stop Attacks Against Mexican Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The government of Mexico Wednesday
asked the United States to prevent armed American ranchers from
attacking Mexican immigrants on U.S. southern soil.
</P>
<P>
Juan Rebolledo, Mexican deputy foreign secretary for North
America and European affairs, showed the request in a letter
addressed to the commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service (INS), Doris Meisner.
</P>
<P>
Rebolledo said that so far attacks by U.S. ranchers against
Mexican immigrants in the American border state of Arizona, summed
up to 24 cases.
</P>
<P>
On two occasions, the ranchers even opened fire against
Mexicans and chased them down the highway, said the official.
</P>
<P>
"These cases are the ones that worry us the most, for these
immigrants are not passing through the properties of the ranchers,
who are waiting for them," Rebolledo said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ranchers claim they had the right to shoot at illegal
who cause damage by entering their properties, but such actions
obviously took place out of their properties, which of course are
illegal, even in the United States, Rebolledo added.
</P>
<P>
He also asked American authorities to punish those ranchers who
have attacked Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Until now it is still unknown whether the ranchers have killed
any illegal immigrant from Mexico, although the ones they capture
are delivered to local immigration authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Arizona border authorities deported some 71,000 Mexicans to
the neighboring Mexican state of Sonora just last month.
</P>
<P>
The illegal entry of Mexican immigrants into the United States
via Arizona intensified last years due to the increase in
watchfulness in California and Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
