<HEADLINE> Czech Currency Hits Lowest Point Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Czech koruna, the country's
currency, dived on Wednesday to its lowest point against the U.S.
dollar since it became an exchangeable currency in 1995, thus
triggering concerns in the country's economic circles.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the dollar and koruna was 1:39.4,
approaching once again the psychological tolerance level of 1:40.
The exchange rate between the two currencies has repeatedly
approached this point in the recent week, mainly due to the recent
weakness in the euro.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the euro plummeted to a new low of 0.9376 against
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that if the koruna's softness continues,
it could hurt the healthy development of the economy, spark
further inflation and damage the confidence in its reliability,
although the current situation could prod the country's export
somewhat for the time being.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Czech authorities are closely watching
the development of the situation. If necessary, the central bank
will intervene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
