<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Reveals Demographics of Home Internet Users in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A study released Thursday
defines the average home Internet user in the United States as a
white man, 33 years old with some college experience and a
household income of almost 67,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. census-based population figures show women outnumber
men 51 to 49 percent, men online outnumber women by a 51 to 49
percent ratio, according to the survey conducted by PC Data Online,
a service to measure e-commerce and Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, African Americans comprise 6 percent of the home
Internet population, while Caucasians make up 77 percent. The
remaining is distributed among Asian, Native American, Hispanic
and other populations.
</P>
<P>
The Net Portrait survey is a quarterly enumeration study to
update the demographics of the U.S. home Internet population.
Nearly 4,000 Internet and non-Internet households were surveyed.
The results are balanced by age, gender, race, education and
household income to produce a representative portrayal of the U.S.
Internet population.
</P>
<P>
"Women continue to exert a stronger presence on the Internet,"
according to the study, which also reinforces the fact that a huge
"digital divide" exists in the United States. Many African
Americans and other minorities have yet to embrace the Internet as
a medium of e-commerce, research and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that almost 58 percent of the U.S.
population owns a computer, and that 39 percent have Internet
access from their homes. In terms of households, this translates
to 58.3 percent of U.S. households that own a computer and 47.6
households that have Internet access. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government Frown on Rebel Army's Plan To Tax on Rich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres
Pastrana Wednesday voiced outrage at the rebel army's declaration
that it will impose taxes on the rich and kidnap those who do not
pay.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the people of Colombia nor I, as the president, are
able to understand FARC's announcement to collect this tax under
the threat of force, and to detain those who do not pay," said
the president.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Public Finance Juan Camilo Restrepo and the
commander of the armed forces General Fernando Tapias also made
public that they share Pastrana's position.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
(FARC), Latin America's largest surviving rebel army, announced a
"Tax Law 002", ordering all individuals, companies and
multinational firms with assets of more than 1 million U.S.
dollars to voluntarily show up in the rebel-held territory and pay
the "peace tax."
</P>
<P>
Those who refuse to pay will be kidnapped, said the rebel army.
</P>
<P>
"FARC's decision goes against peace," said Pastrana, "nobody
understands how they can sign a document committing themselves to
seek an end to hostilities, but at the same time continue with the
kidnappings."
</P>
<P>
General Tapias said the new act made him ask himself whether
the rebel organization is interested in peace or war.
</P>
<P>
"Colombia is not the kingdom of Ali Baba ruled by thieves. The
laws of the state are still in force here," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Public Finance Minister Restrepo also condemned the FARC
statement, warning that FARC might create turmoil and make
investors nervous.
</P>
<P>
FARC, a rebel army founded in the 1960s, now controls up to 40
percent of the country with its 17,000-strong fighters. Eighteen
months ago, the government withdrew security forces from the FARC-
controlled region as a goodwill act to start talks to end the
three-decade-long war.
</P>
<P>
Since then, President Pastrana has been criticized by the
military and civilian organizations for making too many concession
to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Following the FARC's tax declaration, Juan Francisco Mesa,
president of the Non-Governmental Organization "Free Country",
said that "nobody has put a limit to FARC, and that is why this
sort of things happen."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
