<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Property Sector to Recover Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's property sector is
predicted to recover to its pre-crisis level next year as sales
this year are to double from the 1999 figure, a newspaper reported
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Steadily falling bank interest rates are fueling a robust
increase in property sales this year, the Jakarta Post quoted a
leading property developer Ciputra as saying.
</P>
<P>
"With interest rate already falling as low as 12 percent, an
increasing number of people now prefer to buy houses," Ciputra
said.
</P>
<P>
The property sector collapsed in 1998, causing many firms to
default on their debt payments and forcing banks to transfer the
handling of heavily indebted developers to the Indonesian Banking
Restructuring Agency (IBRA).
</P>
<P>
Ciputra said that after two years of languishing in the
doldrums, the property market was bullish amid strengthening
consumers confidence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another property developer Kosmian Pudjiadi of the
Association of the Indonesian Real Estate Companies (REI) shared
Ciputra's forecast, saying the property market has showed a strong
recovery since early this year.
</P>
<P>
"The market expansion would be even faster if the government
could speed-up the restructuring of developers debts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Panangian Simanungkalit, a property expert predicted that full
recovery for the property market is expected only by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Housing sales, the main indicator of the property industry,
would increase to some 90,000 units this year from about 55,000
units last year, Simanungkalit said.
</P>
<P>
"The housing market peaked in 1997 when sales reached 220,000
units. But it would take another three years before the market
fully picks up to the 1997 level." he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
