<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President to Visit East European Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid plans to visit East European Countries soon, according to
Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab.
</P>
<P>
He said presidential staff and the Foreign Affairs Ministry are
now planning the president's visits to Russia, Poland and the
Czech Republic, but the exact timetable is still uncertain due to
ongoing political developments in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing, however, is that the idea to visit Moscow is
cherished by President Wahid and he wants to go there in order to
meet the Russian president at the very first opportunity," the
minister was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Director of the Foreign Affairs Ministry's
Information Department Nugroho Wisnumurti did not rule out the
possibility of the trip taking place this year.
</P>
<P>
"This is more of a technical problem, which depends on planning,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Of decisive importance, Nugroho said, is the fact that Wahid is
determined to hold an Jakarta-Moscow summit and that Indonesia
regards Russia as one of the most important states in the world,
and feels it can play a significant role in promoting stability in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Nugroho said the Indonesian government feels there should be
four world powers -- Russia, the United States, China and Japan --
present in Southeast Asia to guarantee a new political balance of
forces.
</P>
<P>
The president has traveled to more than a dozen countries since
coming to office in October last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
