<HEADLINE> Costa Rica, Qatar Establish Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica and Qatar established
diplomatic relations Wednesday, the Central American country's
Foreign Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to establish diplomatic ties was made by visiting
Costa Rican Foreign Minister Roberto Rojas and Qatar's Minister of
State of Foreign Affairs Ahamad Abdallah Al-Mahmoud.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, which is part of a trip to four Arab
countries, Rojas held two meetings with Ahamad Abdallah Al-Mahmoud.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed to expand cooperation in many fields
and to exchange views and opinions on common positions in
international organizations, such as the United Nations and the
World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their plan to cooperate in a ministerial
meeting of the WTO in Qatar next year.
</P>
<P>
Rojas started his visit to Morocco, Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait
on April 21.
</P>
<P>
The visits to the four Arab countries is considered an effort
by Costa Rica to improve relations with the Arab world, soured in
the 1980s for moving its embassy in Israel to Jerusalem in
opposition to a U.N. resolution.  
</P>
