<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Veteran Julio Salinas to Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Alaves' veteran striker Julio
Salinas announced in Vitoria on Wednesday that he will retire at
the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Salinas won 56 caps for his country and was
part of the Spanish squads at the 1986, 1990 and 1994 World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
He made his international debut in a friendly against the
Soviet Union on January 22, 1986, scoring one of Spain's goals in
their 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
The popular striker made his first division debut for his home
team of Athletic Bilbao on October 3 1982, and won the Spanish
championship that season and the one that followed.
</P>
<P>
After the 1986 World Cup finals in Mexico he moved to Atletico
Madrid and spent two seasons there before transferring to
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
He stayed at the Catalan club for six years, and won four
successive Spanish league medals, a European Championship and a
European Cup Winners' Cup.
</P>
<P>
He entered Alaves who avoided relegation in the last week of
the season after he returned from Japan's Yokohama Marinos.
</P>
<P>
This season he has been mainly used as a second half substitute
but he has still been able to contribute six goals and made his
presence felt in the dressing room as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
