<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Squeezes Denmark 1-0 in Tough Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- With absence of their key
players due to injuries, Sweden beat Denmark 1-0 on Wednesday in a
lackluster international soccer friendly in Copenhagen, Denmark on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Neither the Euro 2000 finalist created many chances as passes
went astray and some tough tackling halted most attacks well
outside the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
The only goal came in the 37th minute when Kaiserslautern
striker Joergen Pettersson controlled a long pass before looping a
shot over Danish goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel.
</P>
<P>
Schmeichel made two good saves as Sweden had the best of the
first half but might be disappointed with his positioning for the
goal.
</P>
<P>
Denmark had one good shot from Brian Steen Nielsen in the ninth
minute and came close to equalising in injury time when Mikkel
Beck's header from a corner was cleared off the line by Olof
Mellberg.
</P>
<P>
The Swedes were without Arsenal midfielder Fredrik Ljungberg,
who suffered a rib injury in last week's UEFA Cup semifinal, and
Celtic striker Henrik Larsson, who has been out of action since he
broke a leg in October.
</P>
<P>
Denmark lacked midfielders Allan Nielsen and Udinese's Martin
Joergensen, both due to minor leg injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
