<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sezer Fails to Win First Round in Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ahmet Sezer, the joint presidential
candidate supported by five parties represented in Turkish
parliament, failed on Thursday to secure 367 votes required to be
elected as president in the first round of balloting.
</P>
<P>
He won 281 votes of total 550 deputies in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to the election procedures, if no candidates win two-
thirds of the votes in the first round, the parliament will hold
the second round of voting on May 1.
</P>
<P>
But Sezer, the presiding judge of the Constitutional Court, led
far away from his strongest challenger, Parliament Speaker Yildirim
Akbulut, who came a distant second with 87 votes.
</P>
<P>
Analyst said that if Sezer maintained his momentum seen in the
first round, he could be elected as the new president in the third
round of balloting.
</P>
<P>
Sezer is the joint candidate of the three ruling parties and the
two main opposition Virtue Party and True Path Party.
</P>
<P>
His score indicated that in the secret ballot, few maverick
deputies repeated their defections seen during last month's vote on
the constitutional amendment for President Suleyman Demirel's
second term in office.
</P>
<P>
Demirel failed to garner enough votes to stay on for a second,
five-year term earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Before Thursday's voting, five party leaders expected to have
Sezer elected by the end of the first three rounds without having
to stage a fourth and final round.
</P>
<P>
In the first two rounds, a candidate needs to win a two-thirds
(367 votes) majority in the 550-seat parliament to be elected
president. If deputies fail to choose a president in the initial
two rounds, 276 votes will be sufficient in the third and fourth
rounds.
</P>
<P>
The third round will take place on May 5, and in case of
failure, two top runners in the third round will compete in the
last round.
</P>
<P>
If no conclusive result comes out in the fourth round, the
parliament will be dissolved immediatly for new general elections
in accordance with the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The parliament chooses the president over a maximum of four
rounds of vote that must end before Demirel's tenure expires on May
16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
