<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Rejects Postponement of Talks on Final Status Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) rejects any postponement of talks on the final status issues,
said a senior Palestinian official on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Voice of Palestine radio, Mahmoud Abbas
(also known as Abu Mazen), secretary general of the Executive
Committee of Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO), said a
lasting peace must address all final status issues.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came three days before Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators are to hold a new round of talks on the last phase
redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank and on the final
status issues, including the status of Jerusalem, water sharing,
refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, with the presence of U.S. mediators, are due to
meet Sunday in Israeli southern port city of Eilat in an effort to
draft a framework agreement on the final status by May and
implement the Israeli redeployment in June under the previously set
timetable by the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum signed last September.
</P>
<P>
However, some Israeli political sources have said that it would
be impossible to solve all final status issues in the short-run
even after the framework agreement is reached by May.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak might suggest postponing the
discussions on the two most thorniest issues of Jerusalem and
refugees for years in spite of Palestinian opposition.
</P>
<P>
The final stage Israeli pullout from West Bank territories is
not related to the final status talks, Abu Mazen argued, adding
that it should be addressed by the interim talks that coincide with
the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords signed in 1993, Israel should withdraw
its troops from the Gaza Strip and all West Bank territories except
Jerusalem, the Jewish settlements and the military sites before
kicking off the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
The PNA now controls 43 percent of the West Bank territories
fully or partially as part of the implementation of the interim
accords.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility that the Palestinian side would agree to
declare statehood over 50 percent of the West Bank territories, Abu
Mazen said the PNA refused categorically the idea, denying that any
side had ever suggested it to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian statehood concerns the Palestinian leadership
which has the right to make any decision," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a plenary session held in Gaza last February, the Palestine
National Council said that an independent Palestinian state with
Jerusalem as its capital would be declared this year.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat also reiterated on many occassions
that the year 2000 would be the year of Palestinian independence
willy- nilly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abu Mazen hailed, on behalf of the PNA, the planned
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon by July in line with the U.N.
Security Council resolutions, pointing out that the Palestinians
presence in Lebanon was transient as the refugee issue was on the
agenda of the Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
Some 360,000 Palestinians live in refugee camps in Lebanon as
a result of Arab-Israelis wars since Israel was founded in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government on April 17 officially informed the U.N.
of its decision to pull out from south Lebanon by July under the U.
N. Security Council Resolution 425 without any preconditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Pullout From Lebanon to Cost 250 Million Dollars: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled Israeli troops
withdrawal from south Lebanon this July will cost at least one
billion shekels (250 million U.S. dollars), a senior defense
official estimated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Amos Yaron, director general of the Defense Ministry, told
Israel Radio that this evaluation is based on the redeployment plan
currently prepared by the ministry, although the final date of the
pullback has not been decided yet.
</P>
<P>
The major spending, according to Yaron, includes building army
outposts and observation bunkers along the 1923 international
border between Israel and Lebanon, and reinforcing the security
facilities of the Israeli northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
However, this budget figure did not cover compensations to
nearly 3,000 members of the South Lebanon Army (SLA), Israel's
major military ally in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israeli defense establishment had planned to relocate nearly 1,
500 SLA militiamen and their families to Arab villages in Israel to
ensure their safety after Israeli withdrawal from the so-called
security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, the Arab communities' leaders had expressed their
opposition to such ideas as these militiamen are regarded by the
Lebanese government as traitors and had been sentenced in absentia
to death.
</P>
<P>
The buffer zone was set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed
aim of protecting its north from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
However, the unremitting armed resistance by Lebanese guerrillas in
the past decades forced Israel to find an exit way from the zone.
</P>
<P>
On March 5, the Israeli cabinet adopted a proposal by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to redeploy Israeli army to the international
border by July, ending the 18-year-long occupation finally.
</P>
<P>
Israel's inner-circle security cabinet is convening on Thursday
to discuss the exact timetable of the withdrawal, and the way to
carry out the redeployment unilaterally without a security
arrangement with Lebanon or Syria, the major foreign power broker
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks had been in stalemate since
January after two rounds of talks in the United States failed to
make progress.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Israel had stated that it will resort to United
Nations' mandate and implement the withdrawal under the U.N.
Security Council Resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
The two resolutions, passed in 1978, call for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli pullout from all Lebanese territories and a
return of full sovereignty to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Middle East Special Envoy Terje Larsen is currently
visiting Israel to discuss with Israeli officials on the
withdrawal. He will also visit Lebanon and Syria for more
consultations in a "fact-finding tour."
</P>
<P>
Yaron did not elaborate on who will pay for the pullback, but
sources in Israeli Foreign Ministry said that Israel is asking the
United States for financial support to implementing the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at several hundred million dollars," Israel's
ambassador to Washington David Ivry reportedly commented on the
estimated total cost of the pullout.
</P>
<P>
"For now there has not been any Israeli request for U.S.
assistance. I expect at some stage it will be discussed but I do
not want to specify when," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000427.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Businessmen To Meet With Cuban Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.S. businessmen will
meet with Cuban officials for the fourth year in a row in the
Mexican Caribbean resort of Cancun and in this capital, a Havana
radio station said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The source, which quoted the Cristobal SRL firm, organizer for
the first time of the meeting, said that this fourth meeting will
start on June 7 in Cancun, and will end three days later in Havana,
to analyze future investments in the island.
</P>
<P>
The company, with headquarters in Italy, assumed the
organization of the meeting after the U.S. government barred the
Alamar Associates firm, with offices in Washington, from
organizing the trip to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleaded to take the U.S. businessmen to Havana to
observe and hear by themselves the true business environment of
the island," said Nikki Cecchi, Cristobal SRL chairman.
</P>
<P>
Cecchi said in a communique issued in Havana that "the
interaction between U.S. businessmen, Cuban officials, and those
of us who already work in the island, must be beneficial for all
the parts."
</P>
<P>
Neither the trip to Havana nor the meeting violate the strict
regulations of the U.S. blockade against Cuba, since all the
expenses will be paid by the Desoft, S.A. firm, an enterprise with
business in this capital.
</P>
<P>
"No other forum permits businessmen to have a unique
opportunity to learn first-hand the Cuban economic reality," said
Kirby Jones, Alamar Associates chairman, who continues as
president of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National Assembly (
parliament), criticized Washington for adopting coercive measures
to prevent investments in the island.
</P>
<P>
The United States intensified the blockade three years ago by
passing the Helms-Burton law that penalized the firms and
executive officers of third countries that would invest or trade
with the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
