<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks Post Sharp Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets all
posted sharp falls Thursday amid fears of higher global interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 lost 77.2 points to close a volatile session
at 6,179.30 after peaking in morning trade at 6,306. Technology
and financial shares bore the brunt of the selling pressure
despite the modest rise on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
Internet service provider Freeserve led the declines with a
loss of 9 percent. Logica, the computer-services firm, fell 6
percent, while chip designer ARM Holdings dropped 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Financial shares suffered on the gloomy interest-rate outlook,
sending Lloyds TSB, Britain's largest consumer bank, down 5.1
percent. Bank of Scotland, the biggest loser Wednesday after
disappointing earnings, fell another 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The telecom firms that had buoyed the market in morning trade
also lost ground. Thus fell 6.25 percent and Cable&AMP;Wireless closed
down 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt closed down 166 points, or 2.26
percent, at 7,221.74, again off its afternoon low of 7,156.
Deutsche Telekom also suffered the worst decline as it closed down
more than 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris, with its heavier weighting of media and
telecom shares, fell 143 points to close at 6,248.86. 
</P>
</TEXT>
