<HEADLINE> Orphans Head Home to China After Successful Facial Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese orphans left the
United States Thursday for China after successfully undergoing
facial surgery by American doctors.
</P>
<P>
The children, along with their caregivers, departed from
Washington's Reagan National Airport at noon. Their air transport
was provided free by Northwest Airlines through its "Friend of
China Program."
</P>
<P>
These children were among the five orphans who arrived on April
8 to receive craniofacial operations at the University of Virginia
(UVA) Health System, which is known for its evaluation and
treatment of all craniofacial problems, including cleft lip and
palate deformities.
</P>
<P>
The Grace Children's Foundation, based in New York, arranged
for the children to receive surgeries in America.
</P>
<P>
Three of the five orphans, ages nine months to two years, whose
deformities were corrected by the surgery have recovered well
enough to travel home, said the foundation's executive director
Nancy Robertson.
</P>
<P>
The fourth child, three-year-old Dang Xiaona, had the most
serious condition, a massive blood vessel tumor in her lip and jaw
which impede her ability to eat. She remains at the University of
Virginia Health System until physicians have finished a medical
evaluation to ensure a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
The fifth child, Qi Gui, three, also will remain for
developmental evaluation to enhance his overall health.
</P>
<P>
The surgeries on both of these children were deemed successful.
</P>
<P>
"We are thrilled that these operations have been tremendously
successful," said Nancy Robertson. "These beautiful children now
have a chance to meet their challenges on a more even playing
field with children."
</P>
<P>
"Our gratitude goes out to UVA, for this wonderful work, and to
Northwest Airlines for helping us transport the children for the
medical care they so desperately needed," Mrs. Robertson added.
</P>
<P>
"Northwest Airlines is proud to have played a role in helping
these wonderful children receive the medical treatment they so
urgently needed to live healthy and normal lives," said David
Mishkin, Northwest's vice president for international and
regulatory affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Although these children may not remember what has happened to
them because of the age, the Chinese people will remember American
people's friendship forever," said Qin Xiaomei, wife of the
Chinese ambassador to the United States, who attended the send-off
ceremony at the airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
