<HEADLINE> Kenya's Tourism Sector in Recovery: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tourism sector has shown
signs of recovery which is expected to continue well beyond this
year, said Kenyan Minister of Tourism, Trade and Industry Nicholas
Biwott here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Donor funding will play a pivotal role in achieving the total
recovery of the industry, he said when meeting with David Villers,
deputy secretary- general of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
According to Biwott, over the past four years, the country's
tourism has undergone a decline mainly due to the deteriorated
infrastructure, particularly roads, posts and telecommunications
services and isolated incidents of insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Other factors attributed to the decline in the industry
included the lack of support programs from the International
Monetary Fund, reduced donor support and the fiscal deficit that
led to high domestic interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his government is committed to turning around
the tourism sector performance by taking a series of measures
including the creation of the Kenya Tourist Board to undertake
destination marketing with new technology such as the internet.
</P>
<P>
The government is also in the process of operationalizing
tourism agreements between Kenya and the member states of the
Common Market of Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his government has granted value-added tax and
duty exemption on fixtures and fitting as well as other
construction materials imported for the purpose of rehabilitation
of hotels and other tourism facilities.
</P>
<P>
Biwott told the guest that his ministry is implementing the
National Tourism Master Plan focusing on the diversification of
both source markets and product range.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned that the European Union has set up an
endowment fund to be utilized by the Kenya Tourist Board in
designation marketing, thereby re-establishing Kenya's image as a
tourist haven.
</P>
<P>
The minister envisaged that as his government attaches
importance to the tourism sector, Kenya will enjoy the growth rate
level of 1994 when the country hosted over one million tourists
with foreign exchange earnings of approximate 400 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The tourism sector is recovering gradually and this favorable
trend will continue into the future, he said optimistically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
