<HEADLINE> Blue Chips Fall But Tech Stocks Rise on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stock ended mixed
Thursday with the Dow Jones industrial average falling on rising
wage pressures and strong economic growth. But the technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index rose.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index closed down 57.40 at 10,888.10, extending its
loss of 179.32 points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Nasdaq index
rose 143.49 at 3,774.03 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 3.
93 at 1,464.92.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip stocks fell after the Labor Department reported
that the U.S. Employment Cost Index rose 1.4 percent in the first
quarter, the biggest advance in 10 years. Investors feared that
the rising wage pressures could prompt the Federal Reserve Board
to raise interest rates in an effort to ward off inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates five times since last June
and analysts expected the board to raise the rates again on May 16
when its Public Market Committee meets on the monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
A separate report on U.S. economic growth increased worries
about higher rates. The Commerce Department said the U.S. economy
grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate in the first three month.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate was still faster than the rate of 3.5 percent
to 4 percent the Federal Reserve regards as pace that can be
sustained without triggering inflation although it was less than 6
percent analysts have expected.
</P>
<P>
But these economic reports did not frighten investors away the
tech sector. The Nasdaq index rose sharply on strong corporate
earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
MCI WorldCom rose after announcing it beat wall Street's
expectations for its first quarter earnings. The company led the
Nasdaq's advance.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 3.86 at 650.45. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 5.66 at 902.09 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 10.34 at 494.58.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,618 down, 1,317 up and 502
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.1 billion shares from 979.71 million
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
