<HEADLINE> Black Sea Economic Cooperation Organization's FMs Meet in Chisinau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Black
Sea Economic Cooperation Organization(BSECO) on Thursday ended
their one-day meeting in Chisinau, Romania taking over from the
Republic of Moldova the chairmanship of the organization.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Romanian Foreign Minister Petre Roman, the new
BSECO chairman, stressed that Romania was taking over the
chairmanship in a very important moment, especially in the
circumstances of holding also the OSCE chairmanship as of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Roman assured that Romania would promote the stability in the
region by an efficient cooperation with all BSECO member countries.
</P>
<P>
"BSECO chairmanship is an advantage for us and I assure you
that Romania will continue the cooperation within this
organization as a valid partner", Roman underlined.
</P>
<P>
Romania will hold the BSECO chairmanship for six months until
November 1, 2000, when the chairmanship is taken over by Russia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by the foreign and assistant foreign
ministers from its 11 member states: Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan,
Bulgaria, Georgia, Greece, Moldova, Romania, Russian Federation,
Turkey and Ukraine, the agenda including issues such as
organization enlargement; the report of the incumbent chairmanship
on the result of EU consultations; BSECO's contribution towards
implementation of the Stability Pact; the signing of the BSECO
seat accord by the incumbent chairmanship and by Turkey; passage
of the next year's budget; and the stage of cooperation with the
Black Sea Bank for Trade and Development.
</P>
<P>
BSECO was founded on June 25, 1992 in Istanbul, to promote
economic cooperation in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
