<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amato Outlines Government Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy's new Premier Giuliano Amato
said Thursday that tackling unemployment and boosting investment
were his top economic priorities, in a speech before the Lower
House of Parliament in which he presented his political program.
</P>
<P>
Amato, who was sworn-in Wednesday by President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi, also stressed that he intended to follow the fiscal
policies of the previous center-left government, headed by Massimo
D'Alema, with "care and prudence", keeping Italy firmly within the
limits set by the euro-zone's Stability Pact.
</P>
<P>
He said that both businesses and families were benefiting from
the fiscal reforms introduced by the center-left and that "if
Italy posts greater tax revenue today with a lower rate of taxes,
that is because there is less evasion thanks to a more efficient
fiscal system."
</P>
<P>
Italian news agency Ansa reported that Amato, who served as
Treasury Minister in the last D'Alema government, also underscored
that the consolidation of Italy's public finances had largely been
completed.
</P>
<P>
He said that, besides the key planks of creating more jobs and
investment, he was aiming for a more flexible economic system, and
would "lift the hand-brake" on the economy.
</P>
<P>
"The government must aim to remove the brakes which render the
economy less powerful and less stable than it should be," Amato
continued.
</P>
<P>
He added that his administration would seek to reduce the
length of time and the costs involved in setting up new firms;
would reform corporate and bankruptcy laws and would encourage the
use of private pension funds, "which are still not taking off."
</P>
<P>
He said that, in general, his government, the 58th in Italy
since the end of the war, would focus on "streamlined legislation
and plenty of action," devoting itself to priority areas,
especially reforms, given the limited amount of time available
before the next general elections, due in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
Amato said that he hoped that there would be a "re-formation of
the majority," which would make it "strong and convincing in its
political values."
</P>
<P>
In other comments, he said that Italy "deserved" to become a
member of the United Nations Security Council under a reformed
system.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Amato and his cabinet will have to undergo a
confidence vote in the Lower House, in which he will need a
minimum of 316 votes if all members of Parliament are present.
</P>
<P>
Amato was named Premier-designate on Friday, in the wake of the
resignation two days previously of D'Alema after eighteen months
at the helm of the center-left.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema quit his job after his coalition suffered a humiliating
defeat in regional elections on April 16, emerging with seven
regions to the center-right's eight and polling about 45 percent
of the vote against the opposition's 51 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
